WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.267 --> 00:00:03.600
JORDAN THIBODEAU: So we're
going talk to Matt and Amanda

00:00:03.600 --> 00:00:04.590
about the book.

00:00:04.590 --> 00:00:06.970
And then we're going to work
in some of your questions.

00:00:06.970 --> 00:00:10.290
So my first question
was, what inspired

00:00:10.290 --> 00:00:12.960
you to write this book?

00:00:12.960 --> 00:00:15.595
MATTHEW MACFARLAND: Well,
I think it was really,

00:00:15.595 --> 00:00:18.940
I've been in the industry
for 18 years now.

00:00:18.940 --> 00:00:20.050
She's been in it about 16.

00:00:20.050 --> 00:00:23.144
And so over the
years you obviously

00:00:23.144 --> 00:00:24.060
hear a lot of stories.

00:00:24.060 --> 00:00:26.309
You experience a lot of
things with different clients.

00:00:26.309 --> 00:00:29.700
But 95% of our clients are
in the real estate industry.

00:00:29.700 --> 00:00:34.010
And so it was kind of a--
when you hear the recurring

00:00:34.010 --> 00:00:36.140
stories, the recurring
mistakes, the lessons

00:00:36.140 --> 00:00:39.840
that people need to learn, it
just seemed like a great avenue

00:00:39.840 --> 00:00:43.760
to put them together and do
it in a way that it was fun.

00:00:43.760 --> 00:00:48.270
Obviously taxes aren't
the most exciting topic,

00:00:48.270 --> 00:00:51.500
and I congratulate you all
for sitting here after lunch,

00:00:51.500 --> 00:00:52.530
listening to a tax talk.

00:00:52.530 --> 00:00:54.780
So good for that.

00:00:54.780 --> 00:00:59.105
But I think it was a good way
for us to do it in a fun way,

00:00:59.105 --> 00:01:03.680
teach people some lessons that
can reach a lot of people, not

00:01:03.680 --> 00:01:06.010
just our clientele, per se.

00:01:06.010 --> 00:01:08.510
But I think that was one of the
motivating reasons for doing

00:01:08.510 --> 00:01:09.610
it.

00:01:09.610 --> 00:01:12.980
JORDAN THIBODEAU: One question
Googlers ask me is what can you

00:01:12.980 --> 00:01:14.470
and what can't
you deduct things?

00:01:14.470 --> 00:01:17.010
And so people say, can
I write off my kids

00:01:17.010 --> 00:01:19.440
for my real estate business?

00:01:19.440 --> 00:01:22.244
Not can I write my kids
off emotionally, but more

00:01:22.244 --> 00:01:23.660
on the real estate
side of things?

00:01:23.660 --> 00:01:24.540
[LAUGHS]

00:01:24.540 --> 00:01:27.250
So maybe you can go over
some of the common deductions

00:01:27.250 --> 00:01:28.977
that real estate investors miss.

00:01:28.977 --> 00:01:31.560
AMANDA HAN: Yeah, I think one
of the main things to understand

00:01:31.560 --> 00:01:34.910
is that anything potentially
could be tax deductible.

00:01:34.910 --> 00:01:37.870
So the question you ask yourself
is if you're spending money

00:01:37.870 --> 00:01:40.670
on something, is it
ordinary and necessary

00:01:40.670 --> 00:01:42.300
for my real estate business?

00:01:42.300 --> 00:01:43.960
So some of the most
commonly missed

00:01:43.960 --> 00:01:48.770
ones would be like car expenses,
travel costs, cellphones,

00:01:48.770 --> 00:01:49.500
computers.

00:01:49.500 --> 00:01:53.270
These are things that we all
use on a day-to-day basis

00:01:53.270 --> 00:01:56.970
personally, but we also use it
to help us in our real estate.

00:01:56.970 --> 00:01:58.460
So there's a common
myth out there

00:01:58.460 --> 00:02:00.920
that we can't deduct
any of these things

00:02:00.920 --> 00:02:02.640
unless we have a legal entity.

00:02:02.640 --> 00:02:04.810
So that's a question
we get all the time.

00:02:04.810 --> 00:02:08.110
Do I have to have an LLC
to deduct certain things?

00:02:08.110 --> 00:02:09.509
Fortunately, the answer is no.

00:02:09.509 --> 00:02:12.150
The IRS doesn't really care
whether you have an entity

00:02:12.150 --> 00:02:12.990
or not.

00:02:12.990 --> 00:02:16.130
What they care about is
whether you have a business.

00:02:16.130 --> 00:02:17.750
And business really
just means do I

00:02:17.750 --> 00:02:20.270
have an intent to make profit?

00:02:20.270 --> 00:02:22.850
In our example, it's the
real estate business.

00:02:22.850 --> 00:02:24.580
So that's probably,
like you said,

00:02:24.580 --> 00:02:26.780
the most common question--
what can I deduct?

00:02:26.780 --> 00:02:28.070
It's hard to say.

00:02:28.070 --> 00:02:31.640
What you can't deduct
would be things

00:02:31.640 --> 00:02:36.270
that are more not necessary
for your real estate business.

00:02:36.270 --> 00:02:38.020
So as an example for
a lot of our clients,

00:02:38.020 --> 00:02:40.900
we have a list of
100 tax deductions.

00:02:40.900 --> 00:02:41.900
It's a little checklist.

00:02:41.900 --> 00:02:44.510
Of course, that's not going
to apply to everybody.

00:02:44.510 --> 00:02:47.850
Not all 100 items will be
applicable to your real estate

00:02:47.850 --> 00:02:49.260
business.

00:02:49.260 --> 00:02:51.525
But the key is to learn to
think about it from a more

00:02:51.525 --> 00:02:52.400
creative perspective.

00:02:52.400 --> 00:02:56.024
And I know all Googlers are
very creative in nature.

00:02:56.024 --> 00:02:58.440
So the question to ask yourself
when you're spending money

00:02:58.440 --> 00:03:02.410
on something is how can I make
this ordinary and necessary

00:03:02.410 --> 00:03:04.678
for my particular
real estate business?

00:03:04.678 --> 00:03:05.844
JORDAN THIBODEAU: Excellent.

00:03:05.844 --> 00:03:09.550
Now, for people who don't have
an investment property, yet

00:03:09.550 --> 00:03:12.660
they're going out to
scout for property,

00:03:12.660 --> 00:03:14.880
can we write those expenses off?

00:03:14.880 --> 00:03:17.940
And do we have to write
them off the same year we

00:03:17.940 --> 00:03:18.690
find the property?

00:03:18.690 --> 00:03:21.589
Or is there a way to hold onto
those for a couple years or so?

00:03:21.589 --> 00:03:23.630
MATTHEW MACFARLAND: It's
a good question, and one

00:03:23.630 --> 00:03:24.860
that we do get a lot.

00:03:24.860 --> 00:03:27.549
So if you are looking
for your first property,

00:03:27.549 --> 00:03:29.340
you are going to incur
expenses to do that.

00:03:29.340 --> 00:03:31.880
You're going to incur travel.

00:03:31.880 --> 00:03:36.380
Maybe you're putting some
expenses down for property,

00:03:36.380 --> 00:03:38.710
to do an inspection
or appraisal, whatever

00:03:38.710 --> 00:03:40.770
it might be.

00:03:40.770 --> 00:03:42.750
If it's your first property
that you're buying,

00:03:42.750 --> 00:03:45.482
all those
preaquisition costs are

00:03:45.482 --> 00:03:46.690
going to get lumped together.

00:03:46.690 --> 00:03:50.200
It's generally what's considered
startup costs of your business.

00:03:50.200 --> 00:03:54.350
And startup costs, you
can write off up to $5,000

00:03:54.350 --> 00:03:56.840
right away, once you
"start" business.

00:03:56.840 --> 00:03:58.650
So with an investment
property, easiest way

00:03:58.650 --> 00:04:00.358
to think about it when
you start business

00:04:00.358 --> 00:04:03.450
is when you actually close on
the purchase of the property.

00:04:03.450 --> 00:04:05.210
So at that point
in time, if you've

00:04:05.210 --> 00:04:07.590
incurred less than $5,000,
you can write them off all

00:04:07.590 --> 00:04:08.320
right away.

00:04:08.320 --> 00:04:09.820
If you've incurred
more than $5,000,

00:04:09.820 --> 00:04:11.470
you take 5,000 right away.

00:04:11.470 --> 00:04:15.160
And the rest you can
write off over 15 years.

00:04:15.160 --> 00:04:16.620
15 years is a long
time, obviously.

00:04:16.620 --> 00:04:17.839
Not a great answer,
and most people

00:04:17.839 --> 00:04:19.500
want to write things
off right away.

00:04:19.500 --> 00:04:23.025
But that's kind of the way
that the tax law looks at it.

00:04:23.025 --> 00:04:24.650
AMANDA HAN: Yeah,
and I think something

00:04:24.650 --> 00:04:27.980
to add-- if you think about it,
what the IRS is really doing

00:04:27.980 --> 00:04:31.140
is they're incentivizing
us to pull the trigger,

00:04:31.140 --> 00:04:33.280
and invest sooner
rather than later.

00:04:33.280 --> 00:04:33.859
Right?

00:04:33.859 --> 00:04:34.900
So they're rewarding you.

00:04:34.900 --> 00:04:37.233
If you're spending money to
learn how to do real estate,

00:04:37.233 --> 00:04:39.080
you're traveling to
look at real estate,

00:04:39.080 --> 00:04:42.590
really the deduction comes
in once you start investing.

00:04:42.590 --> 00:04:44.800
So the earlier you
start investing,

00:04:44.800 --> 00:04:46.341
the better the tax deduction.

00:04:46.341 --> 00:04:47.840
On the other hand,
if you're someone

00:04:47.840 --> 00:04:51.010
who's been taking classes, it's
been years and years and years

00:04:51.010 --> 00:04:53.090
and still haven't really
pulled the trigger yet,

00:04:53.090 --> 00:04:55.500
those items still could
be tax deductible.

00:04:55.500 --> 00:04:58.070
But it's just going to be
delayed into the future when

00:04:58.070 --> 00:04:59.888
you actually pull the trigger.

00:04:59.888 --> 00:05:01.250
JORDAN THIBODEAU: Gotcha.

00:05:01.250 --> 00:05:03.730
One thing I struggle with is
when I go on scouting trips.

00:05:03.730 --> 00:05:06.870
I have all of these receipts and
it's just very time consuming,

00:05:06.870 --> 00:05:08.870
writing all these receipts
down and putting them

00:05:08.870 --> 00:05:10.880
in the right Excel spreadsheets.

00:05:10.880 --> 00:05:13.982
How do you guys manage that?

00:05:13.982 --> 00:05:16.315
MATTHEW MACFARLAND: A lot of
our clients use Quickbooks.

00:05:16.315 --> 00:05:20.520
It's very popular
accounting software.

00:05:20.520 --> 00:05:22.010
We like to say,
it's good and bad.

00:05:22.010 --> 00:05:23.870
It's good because
it's very easy to use.

00:05:23.870 --> 00:05:26.210
And it's bad for us, because
it's very easy for you guys

00:05:26.210 --> 00:05:30.510
to use it, depending on how
well a person utilizes it.

00:05:30.510 --> 00:05:32.510
But it can make things easier.

00:05:32.510 --> 00:05:34.570
One of the things that
we learned from a mentor

00:05:34.570 --> 00:05:38.110
early on was to
hire an assistant.

00:05:38.110 --> 00:05:40.600
You know, and it might seem
kind of like a crazy idea

00:05:40.600 --> 00:05:42.110
for you, if you're just
starting investing.

00:05:42.110 --> 00:05:44.370
But it can be a virtual
assistant, someone like that.

00:05:44.370 --> 00:05:45.130
AMANDA HAN: Or it
could be your kid,

00:05:45.130 --> 00:05:46.350
like what Jordan said earlier.

00:05:46.350 --> 00:05:48.580
If you want to hire your kids
to help with your real estate

00:05:48.580 --> 00:05:50.420
business, what a great
person to help you

00:05:50.420 --> 00:05:51.937
scan receipts and do data entry.

00:05:51.937 --> 00:05:53.770
MATTHEW MACFARLAND: And
that's a good point.

00:05:53.770 --> 00:05:57.010
The IRS, they don't
need to see paper.

00:05:57.010 --> 00:05:59.100
So you can scan a receipt
and toss the receipt.

00:05:59.100 --> 00:06:02.740
So scanning and organizing,
however it makes sense for you,

00:06:02.740 --> 00:06:06.180
whether it's file
holders or on the cloud

00:06:06.180 --> 00:06:09.050
or whatever it is, just find
something that works for you.

00:06:09.050 --> 00:06:11.780
But you just need to be able
to find the receipt if you ever

00:06:11.780 --> 00:06:13.080
need it.

00:06:13.080 --> 00:06:17.340
So I think that's some
big good tips that we've

00:06:17.340 --> 00:06:19.164
talked to our clients about.

00:06:19.164 --> 00:06:20.330
JORDAN THIBODEAU: Excellent.

00:06:20.330 --> 00:06:23.520
Now, you guys are
practicing CPAs.

00:06:23.520 --> 00:06:26.470
So I was lucky to
come across you guys

00:06:26.470 --> 00:06:28.000
through bigger pockets.

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:31.050
But then I get asked
through the Google alias,

00:06:31.050 --> 00:06:33.440
how do I go about
finding a good CPA?

00:06:33.440 --> 00:06:36.065
How do I judge if the CPA
can work with real estate

00:06:36.065 --> 00:06:36.565
investors?

00:06:36.565 --> 00:06:38.400
Do you have any
tips you can share,

00:06:38.400 --> 00:06:41.342
help us identify good CPAs?

00:06:41.342 --> 00:06:43.050
AMANDA HAN: I think
your local community.

00:06:43.050 --> 00:06:44.758
So if you're an
investor, you're probably

00:06:44.758 --> 00:06:46.360
networking with other investors.

00:06:46.360 --> 00:06:48.910
So it's a good idea to ask
who other people are using?

00:06:48.910 --> 00:06:52.910
What's been their experience
in working with CPAs?

00:06:52.910 --> 00:06:56.490
In the interview, ask them
questions about real estate.

00:06:56.490 --> 00:06:58.459
What are you seeing
with your other clients?

00:06:58.459 --> 00:07:00.500
What are your other clients
doing in real estate?

00:07:00.500 --> 00:07:03.120
Do they have issues
with obtaining financing

00:07:03.120 --> 00:07:04.290
or obtaining deals?

00:07:04.290 --> 00:07:06.660
So that will help you
gauge you know how involved

00:07:06.660 --> 00:07:07.770
they are in real estate.

00:07:07.770 --> 00:07:09.390
I know a lot of real
estate investors

00:07:09.390 --> 00:07:12.430
are very creative, so doing
a lot of creative deals

00:07:12.430 --> 00:07:14.605
with a lot of
creative terminology.

00:07:14.605 --> 00:07:15.980
So you just want
to make sure you

00:07:15.980 --> 00:07:18.590
work with someone who
understands the terminology

00:07:18.590 --> 00:07:19.510
you're talking about.

00:07:19.510 --> 00:07:21.450
So if you're doing
a lease option,

00:07:21.450 --> 00:07:24.770
and you're talking to them and
you get really glazed look,

00:07:24.770 --> 00:07:27.010
that's probably a
sign that you're not

00:07:27.010 --> 00:07:28.387
talking to the right person.

00:07:28.387 --> 00:07:30.220
Because they're supposed
to be your adviser.

00:07:30.220 --> 00:07:32.490
So just things like
that, talking to them,

00:07:32.490 --> 00:07:34.410
getting to know how
much they really

00:07:34.410 --> 00:07:36.950
understand your industry.

00:07:36.950 --> 00:07:41.190
MATTHEW MACFARLAND: And I think
just like doctors or attorneys,

00:07:41.190 --> 00:07:43.498
not all accountants
are great and equal

00:07:43.498 --> 00:07:44.910
or do the exact same thing.

00:07:44.910 --> 00:07:46.580
So just because
someone's a CPA and does

00:07:46.580 --> 00:07:51.360
taxes doesn't mean they do
taxes for real estate investors.

00:07:51.360 --> 00:07:53.370
So obviously that can
be question number one,

00:07:53.370 --> 00:07:56.344
and then dig into other
further questions.

00:07:56.344 --> 00:07:58.010
Because we see that
time and time again,

00:07:58.010 --> 00:07:59.700
where people have
hired somebody who

00:07:59.700 --> 00:08:01.560
just doesn't have experience
with real estate, and things

00:08:01.560 --> 00:08:02.059
are missed.

00:08:02.059 --> 00:08:03.680
And sometimes you can fix it.

00:08:03.680 --> 00:08:04.732
Sometimes you can't.

00:08:04.732 --> 00:08:06.650
So it can create
issues down the road.

00:08:06.650 --> 00:08:07.590
AMANDA HAN: Yeah, and
believe it or not,

00:08:07.590 --> 00:08:09.360
we actually have a
handful of clients

00:08:09.360 --> 00:08:11.800
who are CPAs themselves.

00:08:11.800 --> 00:08:15.910
They do taxes, maybe for
manufacturing or R&amp;D stuff.

00:08:15.910 --> 00:08:17.530
And then they have
us do consulting,

00:08:17.530 --> 00:08:19.340
or we actually do the
tax returns for all

00:08:19.340 --> 00:08:20.700
their real estate things.

00:08:20.700 --> 00:08:22.360
So it's perfectly
fine if you have

00:08:22.360 --> 00:08:25.380
lots of different
things going on, just

00:08:25.380 --> 00:08:28.084
to make sure you're speaking
with the right person.

00:08:28.084 --> 00:08:30.500
The thing that is the funniest
to me, I hear all the time,

00:08:30.500 --> 00:08:33.260
is people will call me and
say, oh, you know, I heard

00:08:33.260 --> 00:08:34.740
about this particular strategy.

00:08:34.740 --> 00:08:36.520
And I say, where did
you hear that from?

00:08:36.520 --> 00:08:38.633
And they'll say, oh, I
heard it from my realtor.

00:08:38.633 --> 00:08:40.049
So that's not what
you want to do.

00:08:40.049 --> 00:08:43.289
You don't want to be taking
tax advice from your realtor

00:08:43.289 --> 00:08:44.462
or your dentist.

00:08:44.462 --> 00:08:46.420
JORDAN THIBODEAU: What
are some common mistakes

00:08:46.420 --> 00:08:49.310
that CPAs make in
the tax field when

00:08:49.310 --> 00:08:50.777
they're working our returns?

00:08:50.777 --> 00:08:53.110
MATTHEW MACFARLAND: I think
with respect to real estate,

00:08:53.110 --> 00:08:55.810
believe it or not, one of the
biggest ones that we see missed

00:08:55.810 --> 00:08:57.790
is depreciation.

00:08:57.790 --> 00:09:00.920
So for those of you who may be
new to real estate investing,

00:09:00.920 --> 00:09:04.590
depreciation is you buy a
property, just like a stock.

00:09:04.590 --> 00:09:07.090
You don't necessarily get to
deduct the property right away.

00:09:07.090 --> 00:09:08.370
You've got to write
it off over time.

00:09:08.370 --> 00:09:10.130
And you do that
through depreciation.

00:09:10.130 --> 00:09:12.160
So it's kind of a paper expense.

00:09:12.160 --> 00:09:14.350
You get a certain
amount every year.

00:09:14.350 --> 00:09:17.050
Now, for us, who does real
estate tax stuff all the time,

00:09:17.050 --> 00:09:19.840
it's kind of like
real estate 101.

00:09:19.840 --> 00:09:23.290
But 10%, 15% of
the time we see it

00:09:23.290 --> 00:09:26.270
either done wrong, or believe
it or not, totally just not

00:09:26.270 --> 00:09:27.890
taken at all.

00:09:27.890 --> 00:09:30.266
We had a client a couple
years back that had,

00:09:30.266 --> 00:09:31.640
I don't know, a
dozen properties.

00:09:31.640 --> 00:09:33.590
She'd owned them for
10, 12, 15 years.

00:09:33.590 --> 00:09:35.965
And you look at her return,
she hadn't taken depreciation

00:09:35.965 --> 00:09:38.034
on any of them over the years.

00:09:38.034 --> 00:09:39.450
So the benefit of
the depreciation

00:09:39.450 --> 00:09:41.252
is that it's an
expense you can deduct

00:09:41.252 --> 00:09:43.460
against your other income
from the rental properties.

00:09:43.460 --> 00:09:46.640
So maybe you had
cash flow positive.

00:09:46.640 --> 00:09:48.390
But with the depreciation,
you're at zero.

00:09:48.390 --> 00:09:50.520
Or maybe you're even a loss
on your rental property

00:09:50.520 --> 00:09:52.680
for tax purposes, which
could be a good thing.

00:09:52.680 --> 00:09:55.110
And this person has missed
out for 10 or 12 years.

00:09:55.110 --> 00:09:57.090
So luckily there was a
way we could help her.

00:09:57.090 --> 00:10:01.162
But it was just mind blowing
when you look at it, that you

00:10:01.162 --> 00:10:02.400
haven't been doing this.

00:10:02.400 --> 00:10:04.940
You're a real estate investor
and working with somebody,

00:10:04.940 --> 00:10:06.932
haven't done this for so long.

00:10:06.932 --> 00:10:08.890
AMANDA HAN: Yeah, I think
another thing-- maybe

00:10:08.890 --> 00:10:12.780
not a mistake per se-- but
I think a lot of accountants

00:10:12.780 --> 00:10:18.530
or most accountants are
not creative by nature.

00:10:18.530 --> 00:10:21.670
So we're more critical thinking.

00:10:21.670 --> 00:10:24.380
And so I think a
really good practice

00:10:24.380 --> 00:10:28.400
to get into-- when you
meet with your tax advisor,

00:10:28.400 --> 00:10:32.020
instead of asking them-- like
you were saying earlier-- can I

00:10:32.020 --> 00:10:33.030
write off my kids?

00:10:33.030 --> 00:10:34.280
Can I write off my kids?

00:10:34.280 --> 00:10:37.630
Can I write of this
particular purchase?

00:10:37.630 --> 00:10:40.590
Maybe the immediate answer
is no, you can't do it.

00:10:40.590 --> 00:10:42.630
But instead,
rephrase the question

00:10:42.630 --> 00:10:45.340
to ask, how can I
write off my kids?

00:10:45.340 --> 00:10:46.162
How can I do it?

00:10:46.162 --> 00:10:48.620
Well, maybe you can have your
kids help in your real estate

00:10:48.620 --> 00:10:49.430
business.

00:10:49.430 --> 00:10:51.650
How can I write off
my trip to Florida?

00:10:51.650 --> 00:10:55.320
Well maybe you can have
some pre-determined business

00:10:55.320 --> 00:10:58.930
meetings, schedule things with
local real estate investors

00:10:58.930 --> 00:11:01.410
or potential lenders
working in your deals.

00:11:01.410 --> 00:11:05.370
So just adding that one
simple word, I think really

00:11:05.370 --> 00:11:07.660
helps a lot when you're
meeting with your tax advisor,

00:11:07.660 --> 00:11:10.359
to put them in that
more creative thinking.

00:11:10.359 --> 00:11:12.650
And it's funny because I tell
people this all the time,

00:11:12.650 --> 00:11:13.880
and it's interesting.

00:11:13.880 --> 00:11:17.137
Because sometimes I have clients
that throw this back to me.

00:11:17.137 --> 00:11:18.720
I was talking to
someone the other day

00:11:18.720 --> 00:11:19.875
because they had a
big legal expense.

00:11:19.875 --> 00:11:20.700
This is personal stuff.

00:11:20.700 --> 00:11:21.366
Can I deduct it?

00:11:21.366 --> 00:11:22.290
And I said, no.

00:11:22.290 --> 00:11:23.665
And he's like,
well, the question

00:11:23.665 --> 00:11:24.645
is how can I deduct it?

00:11:24.645 --> 00:11:26.830
So then it was a completely
different conversation.

00:11:26.830 --> 00:11:29.240
JORDAN THIBODEAU: Right.

00:11:29.240 --> 00:11:32.230
So you had a story in
your book about Jeff,

00:11:32.230 --> 00:11:34.110
about him creating the entities.

00:11:34.110 --> 00:11:36.150
Can you talk about
that story and then

00:11:36.150 --> 00:11:39.134
go into common pitfalls
people find themselves

00:11:39.134 --> 00:11:41.550
in regarding setting up entities
in real estate investing?

00:11:41.550 --> 00:11:42.530
AMANDA HAN: Sure.

00:11:42.530 --> 00:11:44.260
I'll let you do that then.

00:11:44.260 --> 00:11:47.800
MATTHEW MACFARLAND:
Well, let's say,

00:11:47.800 --> 00:11:52.520
Jeff is somebody, kind
of a newbie investor.

00:11:52.520 --> 00:11:55.750
And I'm trying to
recall the facts to a T.

00:11:55.750 --> 00:11:59.640
But I think he lost
his job, right?

00:11:59.640 --> 00:12:01.370
And he was getting
into real estate

00:12:01.370 --> 00:12:04.359
and going to different
seminars, educating himself,

00:12:04.359 --> 00:12:05.150
which is important.

00:12:05.150 --> 00:12:07.450
It's a good practice to be in.

00:12:07.450 --> 00:12:10.710
But he got to the point where
he was going to these things

00:12:10.710 --> 00:12:13.050
and he was forking
over thousands

00:12:13.050 --> 00:12:16.817
of dollars on education and/or
creating legal entities.

00:12:16.817 --> 00:12:18.650
One of those-- I don't
know if you guys have

00:12:18.650 --> 00:12:20.650
been to educational events
like that, where it's

00:12:20.650 --> 00:12:23.270
the run to the back of the
room for the next five minutes,

00:12:23.270 --> 00:12:24.440
and you get this great deal.

00:12:24.440 --> 00:12:25.890
And you can create 10 entities.

00:12:25.890 --> 00:12:28.840
And you know, circle the
wagons or whatever it is.

00:12:28.840 --> 00:12:32.350
So he did something like that,
where at the end of the day,

00:12:32.350 --> 00:12:34.302
he was in $10,000?

00:12:34.302 --> 00:12:38.485
He was $10,000 in with
four new entities.

00:12:38.485 --> 00:12:41.358
And when you look back, he
didn't have a single property

00:12:41.358 --> 00:12:42.324
yet.

00:12:42.324 --> 00:12:43.990
AMANDA HAN: So one
of the issues that he

00:12:43.990 --> 00:12:46.390
asked is what is our fee
for doing tax returns?

00:12:46.390 --> 00:12:49.040
Because we met him at a
local real estate club.

00:12:49.040 --> 00:12:50.510
And so I was really
excited when he

00:12:50.510 --> 00:12:52.190
was telling me about all
these different entities.

00:12:52.190 --> 00:12:54.080
I was like, well,
how many properties?

00:12:54.080 --> 00:12:55.370
What are we talking about?

00:12:55.370 --> 00:12:57.940
And that's when we learned he
didn't have any properties.

00:12:57.940 --> 00:12:59.773
And so that's the part
that's very alarming.

00:12:59.773 --> 00:13:02.510
And I think just touching on
a common mistake for people

00:13:02.510 --> 00:13:07.260
starting out-- you do
want to have your entities

00:13:07.260 --> 00:13:08.920
and your strategies in place.

00:13:08.920 --> 00:13:11.200
But you don't
necessarily always need

00:13:11.200 --> 00:13:15.340
to be pulling the trigger
on entity formation, per se.

00:13:15.340 --> 00:13:17.790
So as an example, if you
have no properties yet,

00:13:17.790 --> 00:13:19.480
keep track of your expenses.

00:13:19.480 --> 00:13:21.560
They will become tax
deductible when you do

00:13:21.560 --> 00:13:23.940
start investing in real estate.

00:13:23.940 --> 00:13:25.400
But what we don't
want you to do is

00:13:25.400 --> 00:13:29.450
go out and spend a lot of
money on attorneys and CPAs

00:13:29.450 --> 00:13:31.570
and form all these
entities if you're really

00:13:31.570 --> 00:13:34.530
not going to be able to buy
property maybe until next year.

00:13:34.530 --> 00:13:35.030
Right?

00:13:35.030 --> 00:13:37.040
Because California,
not only do we

00:13:37.040 --> 00:13:40.310
have to pay the attorney
to form the entity.

00:13:40.310 --> 00:13:43.600
The state also charges
us at least $800

00:13:43.600 --> 00:13:47.880
per year, per
entity, just in fees.

00:13:47.880 --> 00:13:49.480
So before you start
making any money,

00:13:49.480 --> 00:13:52.780
we just want to make
sure that the cost is

00:13:52.780 --> 00:13:55.700
justified by the profit that
you're going to be making.

00:13:55.700 --> 00:13:58.116
MATTHEW MACFARLAND: Well, and
think about it for Jeff too.

00:13:58.116 --> 00:14:00.080
He was $10,000 in that
he had already spent.

00:14:00.080 --> 00:14:02.540
And that, I think he had
even borrowed most of that,

00:14:02.540 --> 00:14:03.687
if I remember.

00:14:03.687 --> 00:14:04.770
And he had no other money.

00:14:04.770 --> 00:14:06.800
That could've been
$10,000 as a down payment

00:14:06.800 --> 00:14:09.150
on a potential
investment property.

00:14:09.150 --> 00:14:11.560
Obviously out of state,
probably, somewhere.

00:14:11.560 --> 00:14:13.390
So that's the thing
you got to look at,

00:14:13.390 --> 00:14:16.270
is weighing what do
you have to spend

00:14:16.270 --> 00:14:21.110
and not doing-- what is
it-- paralysis by analysis

00:14:21.110 --> 00:14:25.560
or analysis paralysis, where
we've seen that, where people,

00:14:25.560 --> 00:14:27.760
they feel like I need
to know this much

00:14:27.760 --> 00:14:29.954
or whatever that
much is, they feel

00:14:29.954 --> 00:14:31.120
like they need to get there.

00:14:31.120 --> 00:14:35.050
When in reality,
take small steps.

00:14:35.050 --> 00:14:36.110
Pull the trigger.

00:14:36.110 --> 00:14:37.810
Learn your lessons.

00:14:37.810 --> 00:14:40.062
You can always create an
entity after the fact.

00:14:40.062 --> 00:14:41.520
If you need it for
asset protection

00:14:41.520 --> 00:14:44.570
to title the property
into the entity.

00:14:44.570 --> 00:14:45.250
That's doable.

00:14:45.250 --> 00:14:47.400
It doesn't need to
be done upfront.

00:14:47.400 --> 00:14:51.230
So there's ways to make it work
without spending a boatload.

00:14:51.230 --> 00:14:53.850
JORDAN THIBODEAU: Right.

00:14:53.850 --> 00:14:57.340
So I hear people
talking about setting up

00:14:57.340 --> 00:15:00.500
LLCs for tax benefits.

00:15:00.500 --> 00:15:05.240
Are there additional tax
benefits you gain with an LLC?

00:15:05.240 --> 00:15:06.570
AMANDA HAN: Well, it depends.

00:15:06.570 --> 00:15:08.960
It depends on what you're
doing in real estate.

00:15:08.960 --> 00:15:11.460
Because real estate's
a general term, right?

00:15:11.460 --> 00:15:13.590
So you could be doing
rental real estate.

00:15:13.590 --> 00:15:15.300
You could be doing
property management.

00:15:15.300 --> 00:15:16.964
You could be doing
wholesale and fix and flip.

00:15:16.964 --> 00:15:18.206
JORDAN THIBODEAU: Let's say buy
and hold, because most of us

00:15:18.206 --> 00:15:19.220
do that.

00:15:19.220 --> 00:15:20.980
AMANDA HAN: Yeah,
for buy and hold,

00:15:20.980 --> 00:15:23.929
there is not an
added tax benefit.

00:15:23.929 --> 00:15:26.220
So what that means is if you
buy a rental property down

00:15:26.220 --> 00:15:28.540
the street, you will
get the same write off

00:15:28.540 --> 00:15:31.110
and deductions as if
you own the property

00:15:31.110 --> 00:15:32.435
in your individual name.

00:15:32.435 --> 00:15:35.500
So earlier we were talking
about maybe shifting income

00:15:35.500 --> 00:15:38.400
to your kids, pay them to
help with your receipts

00:15:38.400 --> 00:15:39.870
and bookkeeping on the rentals.

00:15:39.870 --> 00:15:41.650
You can do that
with an LLC, or you

00:15:41.650 --> 00:15:44.490
can do that if you own the
property in your personal name.

00:15:44.490 --> 00:15:46.380
Same with travel expenses.

00:15:46.380 --> 00:15:48.210
If you're deducting
a home office,

00:15:48.210 --> 00:15:51.700
all those are the same
with or without an LLC.

00:15:51.700 --> 00:15:54.930
Now, if you're someone
who's more involved

00:15:54.930 --> 00:15:58.650
in active real estate-- and
some common examples of that

00:15:58.650 --> 00:16:02.380
would be wholesaling, flipping,
you're doing syndications,

00:16:02.380 --> 00:16:04.335
maybe you're a realtor,
also, on the side

00:16:04.335 --> 00:16:06.460
and you're making
commissions income.

00:16:06.460 --> 00:16:08.720
In those examples
there are tax benefits

00:16:08.720 --> 00:16:11.580
of being inside
of a legal entity.

00:16:11.580 --> 00:16:14.040
Because that type of
income is taxed differently

00:16:14.040 --> 00:16:15.220
than rental real estate.

00:16:15.220 --> 00:16:17.740
But for rental real
estate purposes,

00:16:17.740 --> 00:16:19.490
there's not really
an added benefit.

00:16:19.490 --> 00:16:22.470
In fact, there's a cost that we
just talked about, right? $800,

00:16:22.470 --> 00:16:26.090
at least, to the state
every single year.

00:16:26.090 --> 00:16:28.360
But we do have a lot
of clients who have

00:16:28.360 --> 00:16:30.280
LLCs for rental real estate.

00:16:30.280 --> 00:16:32.980
Mostly it's for asset
protection purposes.

00:16:32.980 --> 00:16:35.840
So if you're someone
who has a lot of equity

00:16:35.840 --> 00:16:39.060
in the real estate, or if
you have a lot of net worth,

00:16:39.060 --> 00:16:42.740
it could make sense to have an
LLC, just for asset protection

00:16:42.740 --> 00:16:43.980
reasons.

00:16:43.980 --> 00:16:44.900
OK?

00:16:44.900 --> 00:16:46.691
JORDAN THIBODEAU: Now,
Are there other ways

00:16:46.691 --> 00:16:48.840
to get asset protection
outside the LLCs,

00:16:48.840 --> 00:16:51.860
like umbrella insurance
or anything else?

00:16:51.860 --> 00:16:54.510
MATTHEW MACFARLAND: Yeah,
it's a great question.

00:16:54.510 --> 00:16:56.150
There's other ways, for sure.

00:16:56.150 --> 00:16:57.860
And we talk to our
clients about it.

00:16:57.860 --> 00:17:00.050
One is legal entities.

00:17:00.050 --> 00:17:00.895
That's one option.

00:17:00.895 --> 00:17:02.270
You mentioned
umbrella insurance.

00:17:02.270 --> 00:17:04.884
That's a good option as well.

00:17:04.884 --> 00:17:07.300
One of the tips we like to
mention with umbrella insurance

00:17:07.300 --> 00:17:11.150
is just to make sure that the
activity that you are hoping

00:17:11.150 --> 00:17:13.166
it's going to cover, that
actually the insurance

00:17:13.166 --> 00:17:14.040
covers that activity.

00:17:14.040 --> 00:17:17.550
Because we've talked to even
our own insurance agent,

00:17:17.550 --> 00:17:19.260
like for one of our
rental properties.

00:17:19.260 --> 00:17:21.705
And we want to make sure the
investment covers investment

00:17:21.705 --> 00:17:22.205
properties.

00:17:22.205 --> 00:17:22.980
Yes, it does.

00:17:22.980 --> 00:17:24.800
OK, well, send us the policy.

00:17:24.800 --> 00:17:26.819
We flip to the Exclusions page.

00:17:26.819 --> 00:17:28.900
And lo and behold,
bullet point number five

00:17:28.900 --> 00:17:30.810
says it excludes
investment properties.

00:17:30.810 --> 00:17:32.470
So he obviously didn't know
what he was talking about.

00:17:32.470 --> 00:17:34.767
So I mention that because
I've heard that from clients

00:17:34.767 --> 00:17:37.100
as well, is that sometimes
they look at their exclusions

00:17:37.100 --> 00:17:39.150
and it specifically
mentions it's not included.

00:17:39.150 --> 00:17:42.157
So if you're going to get
umbrella, make sure it covers.

00:17:42.157 --> 00:17:43.990
If it doesn't, make
sure it has a rider that

00:17:43.990 --> 00:17:47.165
covers investment properties.

00:17:47.165 --> 00:17:48.540
AMANDA HAN: Also
debt-- you know,

00:17:48.540 --> 00:17:51.590
debt is a really good
asset protection tool.

00:17:51.590 --> 00:17:55.710
So if you have a property
where it's mostly debt,

00:17:55.710 --> 00:17:59.160
odds of someone suing
and getting access

00:17:59.160 --> 00:18:03.570
to that small amount of equity
is probably not as traumatizing

00:18:03.570 --> 00:18:06.539
as if you had a property where
you might have paid all cash

00:18:06.539 --> 00:18:08.830
or you have a couple thousand
dollars worth of equities

00:18:08.830 --> 00:18:09.710
sitting in there.

00:18:09.710 --> 00:18:11.232
That might keep you up at night.

00:18:11.232 --> 00:18:12.273
JORDAN THIBODEAU: Gotcha.

00:18:12.273 --> 00:18:15.806
I have a specific
question for a Googler.

00:18:15.806 --> 00:18:19.550
"When would an S Corp. Make
more sense than the LLC?"

00:18:19.550 --> 00:18:21.155
The person owns two
investment houses

00:18:21.155 --> 00:18:23.140
and would like to buy more.

00:18:23.140 --> 00:18:24.796
"The growing question
for my husband

00:18:24.796 --> 00:18:27.590
and I is, should we own these
individually, or have them

00:18:27.590 --> 00:18:29.432
in some sort of
business corporation?

00:18:29.432 --> 00:18:30.870
What is the best
way to structure

00:18:30.870 --> 00:18:33.418
owning multiple properties
to optimize taxes paid

00:18:33.418 --> 00:18:35.295
and protect ourself?"

00:18:35.295 --> 00:18:37.170
AMANDA HAN: So that's
a really good question,

00:18:37.170 --> 00:18:39.120
going back to what we
were just talking about.

00:18:39.120 --> 00:18:41.230
For rental real estate,
whether you own one

00:18:41.230 --> 00:18:45.330
or whether you own 100, there's
really not a tax difference

00:18:45.330 --> 00:18:48.586
whether you own it
personally or in your LLC.

00:18:48.586 --> 00:18:50.460
Now, for that particular
person, the question

00:18:50.460 --> 00:18:53.960
about as the S Corporation,
that's a really good question.

00:18:53.960 --> 00:18:56.710
So generally, we
recommend S Corporations

00:18:56.710 --> 00:19:00.200
for active real estate
income, so wholesale,

00:19:00.200 --> 00:19:03.160
fix and flip, real
estate commissions.

00:19:03.160 --> 00:19:08.320
One little tip that we
tell a lot of our clients

00:19:08.320 --> 00:19:11.860
is if you're someone who's
doing active real estate,

00:19:11.860 --> 00:19:15.380
it might make sense
to form an LLC.

00:19:15.380 --> 00:19:18.400
That LLC, we can
always choose later

00:19:18.400 --> 00:19:21.040
on how it wants to pay taxes.

00:19:21.040 --> 00:19:23.660
Meaning a year from now, we can
look back and say, well, how

00:19:23.660 --> 00:19:25.450
did your active real estate do?

00:19:25.450 --> 00:19:26.300
What was the profit?

00:19:26.300 --> 00:19:27.270
Was it $10,000?

00:19:27.270 --> 00:19:29.090
Was it $100,000?

00:19:29.090 --> 00:19:31.800
And from there, we
can retroactively

00:19:31.800 --> 00:19:34.720
file changes with
the IRS to say, OK,

00:19:34.720 --> 00:19:39.190
now I want this LLC to be
taxed as an S Corp or a C Corp,

00:19:39.190 --> 00:19:44.350
or even just as a disregarded
entity, being an LLC itself.

00:19:44.350 --> 00:19:47.030
On the active income side, if
you're a real estate investor

00:19:47.030 --> 00:19:52.590
making active income, the S Corp
does save you roughly 7% to 15%

00:19:52.590 --> 00:19:56.550
in taxes, on average, as opposed
to earning that type of money

00:19:56.550 --> 00:19:58.580
in your individual name.

00:19:58.580 --> 00:20:00.600
So that's where the
tax savings comes from.

00:20:00.600 --> 00:20:02.600
MATTHEW MACFARLAND: Another
tip with the S Corp,

00:20:02.600 --> 00:20:05.010
going back to the
investment property,

00:20:05.010 --> 00:20:06.950
we generally do not
recommend having

00:20:06.950 --> 00:20:11.300
S Corporations own rental
properties, long-term hold

00:20:11.300 --> 00:20:13.187
investment properties.

00:20:13.187 --> 00:20:14.770
The reason being is
that down the road

00:20:14.770 --> 00:20:17.130
it can create adverse
tax consequences.

00:20:17.130 --> 00:20:21.170
So let's say, the S
Corp owns a property.

00:20:21.170 --> 00:20:22.352
Maybe it's got debt on it.

00:20:22.352 --> 00:20:23.060
Maybe it doesn't.

00:20:23.060 --> 00:20:24.590
But you're trying
to refinance it.

00:20:24.590 --> 00:20:27.302
Sometimes the banks are
going to want the property

00:20:27.302 --> 00:20:29.260
to be owned in your title
deed or personal name

00:20:29.260 --> 00:20:30.093
for whatever reason.

00:20:30.093 --> 00:20:32.310
Because maybe you have to
get the loan, or something

00:20:32.310 --> 00:20:32.810
like that.

00:20:32.810 --> 00:20:34.935
Well, if you have to transfer
title from the S Corp

00:20:34.935 --> 00:20:36.500
to the personal
in that situation,

00:20:36.500 --> 00:20:38.340
that creates phantom
income for you,

00:20:38.340 --> 00:20:39.780
as if you sold the property.

00:20:39.780 --> 00:20:41.280
And so that's why
we generally don't

00:20:41.280 --> 00:20:43.480
recommend using a
C Corp or even an S

00:20:43.480 --> 00:20:45.110
Corp to own rental properties.

00:20:45.110 --> 00:20:47.270
That's where owning
in your personal name

00:20:47.270 --> 00:20:49.453
or looking at LLCs
for asset protection

00:20:49.453 --> 00:20:51.720
would be probably the way to go.

00:20:51.720 --> 00:20:53.170
JORDAN THIBODEAU: Makes sense.

00:20:53.170 --> 00:20:54.545
Another question
from a Googler--

00:20:54.545 --> 00:20:57.450
"If I purchase a buy-and-hold
property under my own name

00:20:57.450 --> 00:20:59.910
then later decide to
create an LLC, how tricky

00:20:59.910 --> 00:21:02.900
is it to transfer the
existing property into the LLC

00:21:02.900 --> 00:21:04.370
without paying gains?

00:21:04.370 --> 00:21:07.300
I've heard that this
being done, but I've also

00:21:07.300 --> 00:21:10.769
read that it can be a pain."

00:21:10.769 --> 00:21:12.310
MATTHEW MACFARLAND:
How tricky is it?

00:21:12.310 --> 00:21:14.290
It's not "tricky."

00:21:14.290 --> 00:21:16.840
But it can be done without
any tax consequences.

00:21:16.840 --> 00:21:18.930
So you can own a property
in your personal name,

00:21:18.930 --> 00:21:21.100
decide six months
later to create an LLC

00:21:21.100 --> 00:21:23.730
and want to hold title
for protection purposes.

00:21:23.730 --> 00:21:27.459
You can transfer
title using a deed.

00:21:27.459 --> 00:21:28.750
It should be as simple as that.

00:21:28.750 --> 00:21:30.208
You have to look
at your insurance.

00:21:30.208 --> 00:21:33.000
Make sure that you're adding
the LLC as an additional insured

00:21:33.000 --> 00:21:35.900
on your insurance policy.

00:21:35.900 --> 00:21:37.720
If you have debt
on the property,

00:21:37.720 --> 00:21:40.550
technically that's going to
trigger to due-on-sale clause.

00:21:40.550 --> 00:21:42.292
So a lot of our
clients just leave

00:21:42.292 --> 00:21:44.000
the debt in their
personal name, transfer

00:21:44.000 --> 00:21:46.440
title, keep paying the debt,
and that's not an issue.

00:21:46.440 --> 00:21:46.740
JORDAN THIBODEAU:
Can you explain

00:21:46.740 --> 00:21:47.830
what the due-on-sale clause is?

00:21:47.830 --> 00:21:48.490
MATTHEW MACFARLAND:
Yeah, due-on-sale just

00:21:48.490 --> 00:21:51.776
means on a mortgage-- there's a
clause in everybody's mortgage

00:21:51.776 --> 00:21:53.150
that says, if you
try to transfer

00:21:53.150 --> 00:21:55.740
title of this property,
we, as the lender,

00:21:55.740 --> 00:21:57.420
have the right to
call the note due,

00:21:57.420 --> 00:21:59.450
meaning you have to pay us back.

00:21:59.450 --> 00:22:02.935
Now, I've never heard of a
bank actually doing that.

00:22:02.935 --> 00:22:05.060
But technically speaking,
if you transferred title,

00:22:05.060 --> 00:22:06.130
they could do it.

00:22:06.130 --> 00:22:07.704
But again, most
banks, they'll do it,

00:22:07.704 --> 00:22:10.120
especially if you continue to
pay the mortgage, obviously.

00:22:10.120 --> 00:22:12.720
So now, you can go
to them and ask them.

00:22:12.720 --> 00:22:15.905
Most banks will probably say no.

00:22:15.905 --> 00:22:17.780
Like I said, most clients
just transfer title

00:22:17.780 --> 00:22:21.695
and leave the debt where it
is and just deal with it.

00:22:21.695 --> 00:22:23.570
JORDAN THIBODEAU: Going
back to tax strategy,

00:22:23.570 --> 00:22:27.800
can you explain what
a 1031 exchange is?

00:22:27.800 --> 00:22:32.460
MATTHEW MACFARLAND: Yeah,
so a 1031 exchange, it's

00:22:32.460 --> 00:22:35.196
simple as think about
it back to Monopoly.

00:22:35.196 --> 00:22:36.320
You've got the green house.

00:22:36.320 --> 00:22:37.861
You want to buy the
red hotel, or you

00:22:37.861 --> 00:22:40.200
want to sell the green house
and buy two green houses.

00:22:40.200 --> 00:22:42.320
And you want to do it in
a tax-efficient manner.

00:22:42.320 --> 00:22:43.945
So maybe that first
green house, you've

00:22:43.945 --> 00:22:45.640
built up a lot of
equity and gain.

00:22:45.640 --> 00:22:48.280
If you sell it, you're going to
have a big gain and a big tax

00:22:48.280 --> 00:22:49.040
bill.

00:22:49.040 --> 00:22:51.060
Well, the IRS has
this code-- 1031--

00:22:51.060 --> 00:22:54.050
that allows you to sell that
if you reinvest it and follow

00:22:54.050 --> 00:22:56.984
the rules into new
investment properties,

00:22:56.984 --> 00:22:58.400
you don't have to
pay the tax when

00:22:58.400 --> 00:23:00.287
you sell the first property.

00:23:00.287 --> 00:23:01.870
It basically defers
that tax until you

00:23:01.870 --> 00:23:04.750
sell the new properties
down the road.

00:23:04.750 --> 00:23:06.550
Like, theoretically,
you could continue.

00:23:06.550 --> 00:23:08.365
You could sell one,
buy a replacement,

00:23:08.365 --> 00:23:10.220
sell that one two
years later, and just

00:23:10.220 --> 00:23:11.630
rolling this down the road.

00:23:11.630 --> 00:23:16.160
And theoretically, not paying
taxes for 10, 20, 30, 40 years.

00:23:16.160 --> 00:23:19.430
So it's a great
vehicle for investors

00:23:19.430 --> 00:23:22.750
to keep that extra
chunk of cash that you

00:23:22.750 --> 00:23:25.000
might lose to taxes if you
were to sell your property.

00:23:25.000 --> 00:23:26.310
Because think about it.

00:23:26.310 --> 00:23:28.430
If your tax bill was
going to be $50,000,

00:23:28.430 --> 00:23:31.000
I mean, that $50,000 is a down
payment on another investment

00:23:31.000 --> 00:23:31.970
property.

00:23:31.970 --> 00:23:34.830
So if you can save that now,
buy another property that's

00:23:34.830 --> 00:23:38.080
going to appreciate,
generate cash flow for you,

00:23:38.080 --> 00:23:40.730
you're taking away
that tax drag that's

00:23:40.730 --> 00:23:42.962
going to slow you down
from building wealth.

00:23:42.962 --> 00:23:45.420
AMANDA HAN: Yeah, this is a
really interesting time for you

00:23:45.420 --> 00:23:46.045
to bring it up.

00:23:46.045 --> 00:23:49.170
I just talked to a
new client yesterday.

00:23:49.170 --> 00:23:52.240
The woman is 96 years old.

00:23:52.240 --> 00:23:54.830
And she came in with her son.

00:23:54.830 --> 00:23:57.720
They bought a property
in LA, back in the days,

00:23:57.720 --> 00:24:00.530
for something like $20,000.

00:24:00.530 --> 00:24:03.090
Now it's worth
over $2.2 million.

00:24:03.090 --> 00:24:07.160
And so for them to sell it
outright, pay the capital

00:24:07.160 --> 00:24:08.852
gain between Federal
and California,

00:24:08.852 --> 00:24:10.310
in case you didn't
know, California

00:24:10.310 --> 00:24:11.710
doesn't have capital gains.

00:24:11.710 --> 00:24:13.885
So we're just paying
ordinary income tax

00:24:13.885 --> 00:24:15.970
on the sale of real estate.

00:24:15.970 --> 00:24:20.250
So close to a million dollars
would go away into taxes

00:24:20.250 --> 00:24:23.620
if they were to sell this
property just without a 1031.

00:24:23.620 --> 00:24:25.510
So one of the things
that we're working on

00:24:25.510 --> 00:24:30.190
is for them to sell and to
buy a couple of replacement

00:24:30.190 --> 00:24:32.990
properties, both in state.

00:24:32.990 --> 00:24:34.970
And they're also looking
for out of state.

00:24:34.970 --> 00:24:37.480
So essentially, that
allows them to lock

00:24:37.480 --> 00:24:40.840
in the gain on this
highly-appreciated property

00:24:40.840 --> 00:24:43.400
with zero taxes.

00:24:43.400 --> 00:24:48.710
And because mom
is so old in age,

00:24:48.710 --> 00:24:51.160
the ultimate strategy
would be for mom

00:24:51.160 --> 00:24:55.942
to basically pass away with
these properties in her trust.

00:24:55.942 --> 00:24:58.400
MATTHEW MACFARLAND: You laugh,
but this is a real strategy.

00:24:58.400 --> 00:24:59.066
I'm telling you.

00:24:59.066 --> 00:25:00.190
[LAUGHS]

00:25:00.190 --> 00:25:01.776
AMANDA HAN: Sorry, I don't
mean the ultimate strategy is

00:25:01.776 --> 00:25:02.984
for her to pass away, period.

00:25:02.984 --> 00:25:04.280
[LAUGHS]

00:25:04.280 --> 00:25:07.310
After she passes
away, then the kids

00:25:07.310 --> 00:25:10.690
inherit the real estate
from mom through the trust.

00:25:10.690 --> 00:25:13.110
And what happens
is, at that time,

00:25:13.110 --> 00:25:16.030
the kids can turn around
and sell those properties

00:25:16.030 --> 00:25:18.770
the very next day if they
wanted to, for $2 million.

00:25:18.770 --> 00:25:23.690
And they would get that
money completely tax free.

00:25:23.690 --> 00:25:26.750
So 1031's a very, very
powerful strategy.

00:25:26.750 --> 00:25:29.900
A lot of times for many people,
for many long-term investors,

00:25:29.900 --> 00:25:32.580
it's kind of a let's
make sure we keep it

00:25:32.580 --> 00:25:34.080
in the parents'
name, and then we

00:25:34.080 --> 00:25:38.290
pass it to the kids
with zero taxes ever.

00:25:38.290 --> 00:25:40.570
So the question is
she had $2 million,

00:25:40.570 --> 00:25:42.740
what if the properties
were worth a lot more--

00:25:42.740 --> 00:25:43.530
$5, $10 million?

00:25:43.530 --> 00:25:44.850
That's a really great question.

00:25:44.850 --> 00:25:48.190
Right now, the estate tax,
the first roughly $5 million

00:25:48.190 --> 00:25:49.170
is tax free.

00:25:49.170 --> 00:25:52.420
So for a husband and wife,
this strategy is s up to,

00:25:52.420 --> 00:25:53.975
roughly, the first $10 million.

00:25:53.975 --> 00:25:56.580
You don't have to worry
about estate taxes.

00:25:56.580 --> 00:26:00.390
For those of you with parents
that have over $10 million

00:26:00.390 --> 00:26:02.780
worth of estate
taxes, it's going

00:26:02.780 --> 00:26:04.270
to be a combination strategy.

00:26:04.270 --> 00:26:06.890
Part of that should probably
be gifted to the kids

00:26:06.890 --> 00:26:11.170
now, so that we leave roughly
$10 million in parents' name.

00:26:11.170 --> 00:26:13.600
It's really exciting
to do that kind

00:26:13.600 --> 00:26:15.405
of multigenerational planning.

00:26:15.405 --> 00:26:17.780
JORDAN THIBODEAU: So let's
say I had a personal residence

00:26:17.780 --> 00:26:21.040
and I wanted to do
a 1031 exchange.

00:26:21.040 --> 00:26:23.670
Could I sell that property
and push those funds

00:26:23.670 --> 00:26:25.570
into an apartment complex?

00:26:25.570 --> 00:26:29.040
Or does it have to be
a like kind property?

00:26:29.040 --> 00:26:31.180
AMANDA HAN: So
really good question.

00:26:31.180 --> 00:26:34.820
If you own a primary
home and it's

00:26:34.820 --> 00:26:39.370
highly appreciated in this
area, after the gain exclusion,

00:26:39.370 --> 00:26:43.690
you can only use a 1031
exchange if you turn that home

00:26:43.690 --> 00:26:45.560
into a rental first.

00:26:45.560 --> 00:26:47.050
So if I just have
a primary home,

00:26:47.050 --> 00:26:49.980
it's always been a primary
home, I cannot 1031 exchange

00:26:49.980 --> 00:26:51.600
into some other property.

00:26:51.600 --> 00:26:53.325
I would have to pay
taxes on the gain.

00:26:53.325 --> 00:26:54.950
JORDAN THIBODEAU:
What's the difference

00:26:54.950 --> 00:26:59.512
between retroactive tax strategy
and proactive tax strategy?

00:26:59.512 --> 00:27:01.220
You brought that up
in the book, and that

00:27:01.220 --> 00:27:02.954
was a really interesting topic.

00:27:02.954 --> 00:27:04.370
AMANDA HAN: Well,
there's actually

00:27:04.370 --> 00:27:07.260
no such thing as a
retroactive tax "strategy,"

00:27:07.260 --> 00:27:10.520
because you can't
plan after the fact.

00:27:10.520 --> 00:27:16.630
So really if you're meeting with
your CPA January through April,

00:27:16.630 --> 00:27:18.650
there's really
not any strategies

00:27:18.650 --> 00:27:19.990
going on at that time.

00:27:19.990 --> 00:27:22.420
Really we're just looking
at OK, what did you do?

00:27:22.420 --> 00:27:24.680
And what's the best
way we can present

00:27:24.680 --> 00:27:26.330
what has already happened?

00:27:26.330 --> 00:27:28.740
So in a 1031 exchange
scenario, for example,

00:27:28.740 --> 00:27:31.860
if you sold the property and
then we see you next year,

00:27:31.860 --> 00:27:35.340
well, we can't really do a 1031
because the year's gone by.

00:27:35.340 --> 00:27:38.325
And in fact, the sale
transaction has been closed.

00:27:38.325 --> 00:27:40.780
Proactive strategy
really is just

00:27:40.780 --> 00:27:44.160
meeting with your tax
advisors throughout the year

00:27:44.160 --> 00:27:48.510
before you make these
significant financial or

00:27:48.510 --> 00:27:51.690
personal decisions-- a
decision to leave your job,

00:27:51.690 --> 00:27:54.480
to start a new job, to move
your retirement money around,

00:27:54.480 --> 00:27:56.500
buy, sell real
estate, obviously.

00:27:56.500 --> 00:28:00.210
And so before you enter
into a transaction,

00:28:00.210 --> 00:28:02.000
your advisor can
help you calculate

00:28:02.000 --> 00:28:03.610
what is the tax impact?

00:28:03.610 --> 00:28:05.416
And what are the options?

00:28:05.416 --> 00:28:06.790
Proactive planning
really is just

00:28:06.790 --> 00:28:09.270
another way to say, OK,
well here are your options.

00:28:09.270 --> 00:28:11.810
You can either replace it and
save this amount of taxes.

00:28:11.810 --> 00:28:14.570
Or you can sell the
property, take the cash,

00:28:14.570 --> 00:28:16.190
and run with it
if you wanted to.

00:28:16.190 --> 00:28:19.270
As long as you're willing to pay
the tax, maybe down the road.

00:28:19.270 --> 00:28:23.535
And tax planning doesn't have
to be very in-depth or scary.

00:28:23.535 --> 00:28:26.160
It doesn't have to be hours
and hours of sitting with a CPA

00:28:26.160 --> 00:28:27.112
going over numbers.

00:28:27.112 --> 00:28:28.820
We really encourage
our clients like hey,

00:28:28.820 --> 00:28:31.950
if you're doing anything at
all, send us a quick e-mail.

00:28:31.950 --> 00:28:34.230
You're moving, you're
thinking of changing jobs,

00:28:34.230 --> 00:28:35.480
send us an e-mail.

00:28:35.480 --> 00:28:38.390
And then from that, we can look
at your situation and say, OK,

00:28:38.390 --> 00:28:40.240
does this warrant
a conversation?

00:28:40.240 --> 00:28:41.580
Do we have follow up questions?

00:28:41.580 --> 00:28:43.680
Are there things that
maybe we're concerned with?

00:28:43.680 --> 00:28:45.270
Or maybe there's nothing
we're concerned with.

00:28:45.270 --> 00:28:46.830
We say, OK, thanks
for the update.

00:28:46.830 --> 00:28:48.400
I'll keep it in
the back of my mind

00:28:48.400 --> 00:28:50.740
if something tax-law
wise comes up

00:28:50.740 --> 00:28:52.970
that I think will
impact you, that's

00:28:52.970 --> 00:28:55.160
when communication will be made.

00:28:55.160 --> 00:28:58.050
But it doesn't have to
be a very formal process

00:28:58.050 --> 00:29:00.240
where it's very time intensive.

