00:32:15.948 --> 00:32:17.864
I could see from the
reactions from your eyes,

00:32:17.864 --> 00:32:19.000
it was like, no.

00:32:19.000 --> 00:32:19.773
God, no.

00:32:23.440 --> 00:32:27.110
AMANDA HAN: I think for
high-income individuals,

00:32:27.110 --> 00:32:31.920
it is a good idea to invest in
profit-generating rental real

00:32:31.920 --> 00:32:32.920
estate.

00:32:32.920 --> 00:32:34.640
Because on other
types of investment

00:32:34.640 --> 00:32:37.160
you are making-- let's
say, in the stock market,

00:32:37.160 --> 00:32:40.140
or invest in another
startup company-- the income

00:32:40.140 --> 00:32:42.550
that you get is probably
going to be taxed,

00:32:42.550 --> 00:32:43.970
along with your W-2 income.

00:32:43.970 --> 00:32:45.870
So that's going to be
at a high tax rate.

00:32:45.870 --> 00:32:48.050
Versus rental real
estate, at a minimum,

00:32:48.050 --> 00:32:50.570
it does give you a lot of tax
write offs-- a lot of the ones

00:32:50.570 --> 00:32:52.520
we talked about
earlier-- in addition

00:32:52.520 --> 00:32:55.640
to what Matt mentioned
about depreciation.

00:32:55.640 --> 00:32:59.400
So it's not uncommon for us
to see high-income individuals

00:32:59.400 --> 00:33:03.090
invest in real estate
with the result being

00:33:03.090 --> 00:33:05.910
that at least the
rental income is coming

00:33:05.910 --> 00:33:08.760
to them on a tax-free basis.

00:33:08.760 --> 00:33:11.160
So that's the first
tier we want to get to,

00:33:11.160 --> 00:33:12.802
is at least tax-free
rental income.

00:33:12.802 --> 00:33:14.260
And that is available,
I would say,

00:33:14.260 --> 00:33:16.389
to the majority of
real estate investors.

00:33:16.389 --> 00:33:17.930
If you're working
with the right CPA,

00:33:17.930 --> 00:33:20.550
there should be enough
deductions pulled out

00:33:20.550 --> 00:33:22.274
so you can reach that level.

00:33:22.274 --> 00:33:23.940
Then the next question
just becomes, OK,

00:33:23.940 --> 00:33:27.420
if I do such a good job at
capturing my expenses that I

00:33:27.420 --> 00:33:29.840
actually show a loss
on my tax return,

00:33:29.840 --> 00:33:34.210
how can I use that to offset
the taxable income from my W-2,

00:33:34.210 --> 00:33:35.560
for example?

00:33:35.560 --> 00:33:37.860
And so one of the
great ways to do

00:33:37.860 --> 00:33:41.110
that is if you-- or if you're
married, you have a spouse--

00:33:41.110 --> 00:33:43.580
can qualify as a real
estate professional.

00:33:43.580 --> 00:33:45.940
By being a real
estate professional,

00:33:45.940 --> 00:33:48.510
all that means in a
tax world is that you

00:33:48.510 --> 00:33:52.360
can use the rental losses to
now offset the taxable income

00:33:52.360 --> 00:33:54.069
from your W-2 as well.

00:33:54.069 --> 00:33:55.610
So instead of seeing
them separately,

00:33:55.610 --> 00:33:57.447
it's now all rolled into one.

00:33:57.447 --> 00:33:59.280
MATTHEW MACFARLAND: So
a big picture-- maybe

00:33:59.280 --> 00:34:00.738
you've got enough
rental properties

00:34:00.738 --> 00:34:03.074
that, like we talked about,
are cash flow positive.

00:34:03.074 --> 00:34:05.490
But we can generate enough
depreciation in the home office

00:34:05.490 --> 00:34:09.416
deductions, hiring your kids,
other strategies to generate

00:34:09.416 --> 00:34:11.219
that the expenses are
more than the income

00:34:11.219 --> 00:34:12.627
so you have a loss now.

00:34:12.627 --> 00:34:14.460
But really, you're still
cash-flow positive.

00:34:14.460 --> 00:34:17.110
But now we're just utilizing
deductions for all the things

00:34:17.110 --> 00:34:18.632
that you already are paying for.

00:34:18.632 --> 00:34:21.090
And then you can use that to
offset the income taxes you're

00:34:21.090 --> 00:34:21.960
paying on your W-2.

00:34:21.960 --> 00:34:23.370
That's the ultimate goal.

00:34:23.370 --> 00:34:25.039
And that's where if
you can get someone

00:34:25.039 --> 00:34:27.580
in the family that can qualify
as a real estate professional,

00:34:27.580 --> 00:34:29.540
that would allow you to do that.

00:34:29.540 --> 00:34:31.889
Or go marry somebody that's
a real estate professional.

00:34:31.889 --> 00:34:35.949
You know, marriage
counseling here, you know?

00:34:35.949 --> 00:34:37.409
So that's one way.

00:34:37.409 --> 00:34:40.270
I mean he talked about other
things for high-income earners.

00:34:40.270 --> 00:34:42.480
One of the things we talk
to a lot of clients about,

00:34:42.480 --> 00:34:44.396
because it's something
we're passionate about.

00:34:44.396 --> 00:34:46.969
I know you said, you give
back a lot of your time.

00:34:46.969 --> 00:34:48.739
You can incorporate
charitable giving

00:34:48.739 --> 00:34:50.360
with real estate investing.

00:34:50.360 --> 00:34:52.440
There's lots of different
strategies out there.

00:34:52.440 --> 00:34:55.199
I mean, obviously you can give
straight cash to a charity.

00:34:55.199 --> 00:34:57.550
You can give household
goods to charity.

00:34:57.550 --> 00:34:58.390
You can do all that.

00:34:58.390 --> 00:34:59.931
But there's more
advanced strategies,

00:34:59.931 --> 00:35:01.960
where you can put
money in things

00:35:01.960 --> 00:35:03.220
that are a charitable trust.

00:35:03.220 --> 00:35:04.110
You can put money in.

00:35:04.110 --> 00:35:07.620
You can get a donation deduction
for the money going in.

00:35:07.620 --> 00:35:10.540
And then the trust actually goes
out and buys rental properties

00:35:10.540 --> 00:35:13.030
and generates cash flow, and
then donates the cash flow

00:35:13.030 --> 00:35:13.930
to charities.

00:35:13.930 --> 00:35:17.180
And so it's a way for you
to still buy real estate,

00:35:17.180 --> 00:35:18.430
build wealth.

00:35:18.430 --> 00:35:20.870
But at the same time,
get tax deductions now,

00:35:20.870 --> 00:35:23.250
if maybe you can't qualify as
a real estate professional,

00:35:23.250 --> 00:35:25.960
let's say, you're still
offsetting the high W-2 income.

00:35:25.960 --> 00:35:28.706
So there's definitely
ways to do it.

00:35:28.706 --> 00:35:30.330
And sometimes it just
involves changing

00:35:30.330 --> 00:35:31.580
the fact pattern a little bit.

00:35:31.580 --> 00:35:33.872
People have to be willing to
change their fact pattern.

00:35:33.872 --> 00:35:36.413
AMANDA HAN: I was going to say,
about the charitable planning

00:35:36.413 --> 00:35:38.930
strategy, I mean, it's a
somewhat advanced strategy.

00:35:38.930 --> 00:35:41.480
But one of the things that a
lot of people like about that

00:35:41.480 --> 00:35:46.190
is at the end of the day,
you do own the asset again.

00:35:46.190 --> 00:35:49.110
So you know, if what you donated
into the charitable trust

00:35:49.110 --> 00:35:51.980
is three rental
properties, for example,

00:35:51.980 --> 00:35:55.130
at the end of the trust term,
those three properties revert

00:35:55.130 --> 00:35:57.440
back to your
ownership or your LLC,

00:35:57.440 --> 00:35:59.800
or your estate,
however you dictate it.

00:35:59.800 --> 00:36:01.214
And so that makes sense.

00:36:01.214 --> 00:36:02.630
A lot of times,
if we have clients

00:36:02.630 --> 00:36:06.820
who have an extraordinary year--
maybe stock options or payouts,

00:36:06.820 --> 00:36:09.922
or something like that-- and
they want to buy real estate.

00:36:09.922 --> 00:36:12.380
They don't necessarily need
the income from the real estate

00:36:12.380 --> 00:36:13.025
just yet.

00:36:13.025 --> 00:36:14.150
But they do want the asset.

00:36:14.150 --> 00:36:16.233
They do want to own the
real estate in the future.

00:36:16.233 --> 00:36:19.130
It's a really great way to get
a very large write off in a year

00:36:19.130 --> 00:36:23.504
where you have a significant
increase of income.

00:36:23.504 --> 00:36:25.170
AUDIENCE: Actually,
I had two questions.

