00:36:31.054 --> 00:36:35.800
And what would we need
the umbrella policy for,

00:36:35.800 --> 00:36:39.121
in terms of the rental property?

00:36:39.121 --> 00:36:40.620
MATTHEW MACFARLAND:
So the question,

00:36:40.620 --> 00:36:42.328
what do you need the
umbrella policy for,

00:36:42.328 --> 00:36:43.550
for the rental properties?

00:36:43.550 --> 00:36:47.574
It's more for the exposure.

00:36:47.574 --> 00:36:48.990
And obviously we're
not attorneys.

00:36:48.990 --> 00:36:50.281
We're not litigation attorneys.

00:36:50.281 --> 00:36:53.280
But it's more of a if the
crap hits the fan, you know,

00:36:53.280 --> 00:36:55.945
somebody trips and falls
on your property or--

00:36:55.945 --> 00:36:57.320
AUDIENCE: On the
rental property?

00:36:57.320 --> 00:36:59.445
MATTHEW MACFARLAND: Yeah,
on your rental property--

00:36:59.445 --> 00:37:01.850
falls off a railing or decides
to see you for some reason

00:37:01.850 --> 00:37:06.740
and can make the argument,
in a court of law,

00:37:06.740 --> 00:37:08.600
they should be
entitled to something.

00:37:08.600 --> 00:37:10.900
That's where the umbrella
insurance, theoretically,

00:37:10.900 --> 00:37:13.060
would kick in to
protect you, for having

00:37:13.060 --> 00:37:17.720
to fork out $50,000 for
some plaintiff or something.

00:37:17.720 --> 00:37:20.160
AUDIENCE: Sorry, actually, but
my most important question.

00:37:20.160 --> 00:37:22.820
My kind of funny personal thing.

00:37:22.820 --> 00:37:25.820
But my sister is breaking up
with her boyfriend in Atlanta.

00:37:25.820 --> 00:37:27.490
And they own a condominium.

00:37:27.490 --> 00:37:28.580
She owns 1/3.

00:37:28.580 --> 00:37:29.289
He owns 2/3.

00:37:29.289 --> 00:37:31.330
She doesn't have a lot of
money, a lot of income.

00:37:31.330 --> 00:37:36.510
So I'm going to buy him out, his
2/3 property, his 2/3 portion.

00:37:36.510 --> 00:37:39.310
How should I structure that,
in terms of my income tax?

00:37:39.310 --> 00:37:41.460
Or how would a
person, anybody here,

00:37:41.460 --> 00:37:43.390
buying a property
with a sibling,

00:37:43.390 --> 00:37:45.890
how can you do that
so that you can maybe

00:37:45.890 --> 00:37:48.400
treat that as
rental income and I

00:37:48.400 --> 00:37:50.880
could get some
kind of deduction,

00:37:50.880 --> 00:37:53.264
but she can continue
having partial ownership?

00:37:53.264 --> 00:37:53.930
AMANDA HAN: Hmm.

00:37:53.930 --> 00:37:54.890
That's a really good question.

00:37:54.890 --> 00:37:57.470
So I'm assuming your sister
is going to still live there

00:37:57.470 --> 00:37:58.790
as her primary home.

00:37:58.790 --> 00:38:01.310
So generally, the way we set
up on the tax returns side,

00:38:01.310 --> 00:38:05.140
is you would claim the
1/2 of it, or 2/3 of that,

00:38:05.140 --> 00:38:08.350
as rental income,
rental expenses.

00:38:08.350 --> 00:38:09.950
And then her
portion of that, she

00:38:09.950 --> 00:38:11.820
would just claim as a
regular primary home.

00:38:11.820 --> 00:38:13.945
So she would have a little
bit of mortgage interest

00:38:13.945 --> 00:38:15.570
and property taxes.

00:38:15.570 --> 00:38:21.240
Now, with respect to how
you hold title, again,

00:38:21.240 --> 00:38:23.130
if it's a rental
property, we're not

00:38:23.130 --> 00:38:25.370
very too concerned with taxes.

00:38:25.370 --> 00:38:27.380
There is no tax benefit
or detriment either way.

00:38:27.380 --> 00:38:29.850
Keep in mind, even though
it's an out-of-state property,

00:38:29.850 --> 00:38:32.650
and if you formed an
out-of-state LLC, just

00:38:32.650 --> 00:38:34.960
by the fact that you're
a California resident

00:38:34.960 --> 00:38:39.000
means that you will have to pay
$800 for that out-of-state LLC

00:38:39.000 --> 00:38:39.540
here.

00:38:39.540 --> 00:38:42.760
So really, the question
is how comfortable are you

00:38:42.760 --> 00:38:45.500
with going into partnership with
your sister, the odds of you

00:38:45.500 --> 00:38:47.430
guys suing each other?

00:38:47.430 --> 00:38:50.550
If you guys are close, the odds
of your sister as your tenant,

00:38:50.550 --> 00:38:53.650
suing you, is probably very low.

00:38:53.650 --> 00:38:55.880
Yeah, the question is
if you're not really

00:38:55.880 --> 00:38:58.480
charging a lot of rent, how
does that work as a rental?

00:38:58.480 --> 00:39:00.680
So on the tax side, you do
have to charge her rent.

00:39:00.680 --> 00:39:03.180
Otherwise you
don't have a stance

00:39:03.180 --> 00:39:05.000
to take as a rental property.

00:39:05.000 --> 00:39:07.300
It could be below market
value, because it's

00:39:07.300 --> 00:39:08.580
a partial ownership.

00:39:08.580 --> 00:39:09.660
That's perfectly fine.

00:39:09.660 --> 00:39:11.880
So maybe she pays
you $300 of rent.

00:39:11.880 --> 00:39:14.502
But you'll still
get your 1/2 or 2/3

00:39:14.502 --> 00:39:16.210
of mortgage interest
and stuff like that.

00:39:16.210 --> 00:39:18.220
AUDIENCE: But isn't
that more of a given?

00:39:18.220 --> 00:39:19.470
MATTHEW MACFARLAND: It can be.

00:39:19.470 --> 00:39:22.180
Gift taxes can definitely
come into situations

00:39:22.180 --> 00:39:25.000
where family member's involved
and you have transactions

00:39:25.000 --> 00:39:25.707
or below market.

00:39:25.707 --> 00:39:27.540
So there's definitely
things to think about.

00:39:27.540 --> 00:39:29.147
The other thing I
was thinking was

00:39:29.147 --> 00:39:30.980
in terms of how you
structure the ownership.

00:39:30.980 --> 00:39:33.360
You might want to look at
economically, outside of taxes,

00:39:33.360 --> 00:39:37.930
economically look at do you
get a better deal buying it all

00:39:37.930 --> 00:39:40.461
yourself, from a mortgage
standpoint or a financing

00:39:40.461 --> 00:39:40.960
perspective?

00:39:40.960 --> 00:39:42.001
Or maybe it flip flopped.

00:39:42.001 --> 00:39:42.992
Maybe your sister does.

00:39:42.992 --> 00:39:44.700
So those are other
things, outside taxes,

00:39:44.700 --> 00:39:47.980
things to think about
too, just how you actually

00:39:47.980 --> 00:39:49.970
buy the property.

00:39:49.970 --> 00:39:53.370
AUDIENCE: I was curious if you
do much with family limited

00:39:53.370 --> 00:39:54.095
partnerships?

00:39:54.095 --> 00:39:55.720
This is something I
read about recently

00:39:55.720 --> 00:39:59.850
that was pretty fascinating
for protecting your assets,

00:39:59.850 --> 00:40:04.462
as well as shielding
your taxable inheritance.

00:40:04.462 --> 00:40:06.670
MATTHEW MACFARLAND: Yeah,
family limited partnerships

00:40:06.670 --> 00:40:08.620
are very, very popular.

00:40:08.620 --> 00:40:11.910
They've been around, tried
and true in the tax world,

00:40:11.910 --> 00:40:16.320
in the tax court for decades.

00:40:16.320 --> 00:40:19.710
They are very common
with families that

00:40:19.710 --> 00:40:21.380
have a large amount of assets.

00:40:21.380 --> 00:40:24.640
So we were talking about
the $10 million earlier.

00:40:24.640 --> 00:40:26.710
Family limited
partnerships can be

00:40:26.710 --> 00:40:28.820
very helpful in those
situations, where you're

00:40:28.820 --> 00:40:31.960
trying to-- as Amanda
was mentioning-- kind

00:40:31.960 --> 00:40:34.990
of gifting partial ownership
of properties over time,

00:40:34.990 --> 00:40:36.180
to your kids.

00:40:36.180 --> 00:40:42.270
So that can be a way to start
taking a portion of the asset

00:40:42.270 --> 00:40:45.445
out of the parent's estate,
so that they're decreasing

00:40:45.445 --> 00:40:47.570
their value of their estate
to maybe try and get it

00:40:47.570 --> 00:40:49.012
under the $10 million.

00:40:49.012 --> 00:40:52.171
But at the same time, they're
still controlling the asset.

00:40:52.171 --> 00:40:53.920
But the kids are
involved in the business.

00:40:53.920 --> 00:40:55.690
Because in the
limited partnership,

00:40:55.690 --> 00:40:58.540
generally it's four,
five, six family members

00:40:58.540 --> 00:40:59.594
are all the partners.

00:40:59.594 --> 00:41:03.160
And so that's where
it's used a lot.

00:41:03.160 --> 00:41:06.760
There's ways to use it to
shift income to different kids

00:41:06.760 --> 00:41:07.290
as well.

00:41:07.290 --> 00:41:09.492
So there's a lot
of benefits for it.

00:41:09.492 --> 00:41:10.950
But from a big-picture
perspective,

00:41:10.950 --> 00:41:13.580
we see it used a lot
with the families that

00:41:13.580 --> 00:41:16.689
have $5, $10, $15
million-plus in assets.

00:41:16.689 --> 00:41:17.980
AUDIENCE: The asset protection?

00:41:17.980 --> 00:41:20.240
MATTHEW MACFARLAND: Yeah,
the question was, in terms

00:41:20.240 --> 00:41:24.430
of asset protection, can it be
a better vehicle for investing

00:41:24.430 --> 00:41:27.150
within the family than an LLC?

00:41:27.150 --> 00:41:30.366
I think that's probably more
of a question for an attorney.

00:41:30.366 --> 00:41:33.550
And I think it
probably could be.

00:41:33.550 --> 00:41:36.390
But theoretically, both
come with "limited liability

00:41:36.390 --> 00:41:36.890
protection."

00:41:36.890 --> 00:41:40.940
So I'd really have to
defer that to an attorney.

00:41:40.940 --> 00:41:44.360
AMANDA HAN: I think practically
speaking, the vast majority

00:41:44.360 --> 00:41:48.940
of our clients who own rental
real estate use LLCs rather

00:41:48.940 --> 00:41:51.990
than family limited
partnerships, are

00:41:51.990 --> 00:41:53.680
older clients who've
been in real estate

00:41:53.680 --> 00:41:56.540
for many, many years tend to
use family limited partnerships.

00:41:56.540 --> 00:41:59.110
And I think partly because the
nature of the estate planning

00:41:59.110 --> 00:42:00.010
component.

00:42:00.010 --> 00:42:03.300
And then partly just
because back in the days,

00:42:03.300 --> 00:42:05.060
FLPs were much more prevalent.

00:42:05.060 --> 00:42:09.240
And now LLCs are typically
more preferred by attorneys

00:42:09.240 --> 00:42:10.597
for asset protection.

00:42:10.597 --> 00:42:12.930
MATTHEW MACFARLAND: And another
thing worth pointing out

00:42:12.930 --> 00:42:15.072
is with the limited
partnership, technically,

00:42:15.072 --> 00:42:17.030
with every one of them,
you have to have what's

00:42:17.030 --> 00:42:18.365
called a general partner.

00:42:18.365 --> 00:42:19.820
The general partner
is the person

00:42:19.820 --> 00:42:24.050
or the entity that's going
to have unlimited liability

00:42:24.050 --> 00:42:24.559
exposure.

00:42:24.559 --> 00:42:26.600
So a lot of times, with
the limited partnerships,

00:42:26.600 --> 00:42:30.380
you have to create a corporation
to be the general partner,

00:42:30.380 --> 00:42:32.596
to hold 1%, 5%, 10%.

00:42:32.596 --> 00:42:33.720
Obviously that can be done.

00:42:33.720 --> 00:42:36.190
It's not earth shattering.

00:42:36.190 --> 00:42:37.940
But it's one other
thing you've got to do.

00:42:37.940 --> 00:42:39.856
It's another corporation
you've got to create.

00:42:39.856 --> 00:42:43.009
With an LLC, you don't have to
have a general partner, per se.

