gain free, or I cash
out some of the money

00:43:05.430 --> 00:43:07.900
and then you do
house improvements

00:43:07.900 --> 00:43:12.855
and get the benefits of
the mortgage tax deduction?

00:43:12.855 --> 00:43:17.320
Or compare with use the cash or
the money on rental property,

00:43:17.320 --> 00:43:21.330
and I heard I can also get
the deduction on the mortgage

00:43:21.330 --> 00:43:22.280
interest.

00:43:22.280 --> 00:43:24.260
So compare these
three strategies.

00:43:24.260 --> 00:43:28.290
Which one is the most tax
efficient in the longer run?

00:43:28.290 --> 00:43:32.070
AMANDA HAN: Well, I think if
your primary home is highly

00:43:32.070 --> 00:43:35.590
appreciated, from a
tax perspective, first

00:43:35.590 --> 00:43:39.750
and foremost, is to lock in that
$250,000 or $500,000 tax free.

00:43:39.750 --> 00:43:41.160
And so you can do that.

00:43:41.160 --> 00:43:43.676
Let's say, you sold
your house today.

00:43:43.676 --> 00:43:45.050
You've been in
there for a couple

00:43:45.050 --> 00:43:47.252
years, two to three years.

00:43:47.252 --> 00:43:47.960
Then that's fine.

00:43:47.960 --> 00:43:50.720
You can move out, sell
it, get the tax-free gain,

00:43:50.720 --> 00:43:53.000
take the cash, and then do
whatever you want with it.

00:43:53.000 --> 00:43:55.620
Buy other rental properties,
buy a new primary home.

00:43:55.620 --> 00:43:56.850
That's all perfectly fine.

00:43:56.850 --> 00:44:00.300
If you feel like that home has
more appreciation potential--

00:44:00.300 --> 00:44:03.550
you want to keep it, but you
want to turn it into a rental,

00:44:03.550 --> 00:44:05.610
you can do that as well.

00:44:05.610 --> 00:44:09.190
We do recommend, though, that
if you move out of your home,

00:44:09.190 --> 00:44:13.059
you sell it within three years
of turning it into a rental.

00:44:13.059 --> 00:44:15.100
Because you have that
additional three-year grace

00:44:15.100 --> 00:44:17.530
period, where you have
that rental income.

00:44:17.530 --> 00:44:19.640
And when you go
sell, you still can

00:44:19.640 --> 00:44:22.381
tap into that $250,000 or
$500,000 of capital gains.

00:44:22.381 --> 00:44:24.380
MATTHEW MACFARLAND: So
even though you moved out

00:44:24.380 --> 00:44:28.020
three years ago, you still get
to use that primary residence

00:44:28.020 --> 00:44:29.520
tax-free exclusion,
even though it's

00:44:29.520 --> 00:44:31.740
been a rental property
for the last three years.

00:44:31.740 --> 00:44:33.426
So you can even do that.

00:44:33.426 --> 00:44:35.175
And then you can tack
on the 1031 exchange

00:44:35.175 --> 00:44:36.590
that we talked about earlier.

00:44:36.590 --> 00:44:40.100
So you can actually take
your $500,000 tax-free cash

00:44:40.100 --> 00:44:42.270
in your pocket,
do a 1031 exchange

00:44:42.270 --> 00:44:44.650
on the rest of the property,
buy a replacement investment

00:44:44.650 --> 00:44:46.760
property, and then
continue to roll that,

00:44:46.760 --> 00:44:49.130
but still get your tax-free
money in your pocket.

00:44:49.130 --> 00:44:52.040
So we've had clients use that
multiple times and it works out

00:44:52.040 --> 00:44:52.540
really well.

00:44:52.540 --> 00:44:52.820
AUDIENCE: Can you do both?

00:44:52.820 --> 00:44:53.850
MATTHEW MACFARLAND:
Yeah, you can do both.

00:44:53.850 --> 00:44:54.473
It's awesome.

00:44:54.473 --> 00:44:55.420
AMANDA HAN: Yeah.

00:44:55.420 --> 00:44:56.878
MATTHEW MACFARLAND:
So the question

00:44:56.878 --> 00:45:00.610
is if I keep the property,
refinance it, use the money

00:45:00.610 --> 00:45:02.560
to do home
improvements, to improve

00:45:02.560 --> 00:45:05.545
that property, or refinancing,
use that money to go out

00:45:05.545 --> 00:45:07.040
and buy an investment property.

00:45:07.040 --> 00:45:09.820
And I think from an
accountant's perspective,

00:45:09.820 --> 00:45:11.920
it's going to come
down to numbers.

00:45:11.920 --> 00:45:14.044
It's like, if you're going
to improve the property,

00:45:14.044 --> 00:45:16.550
what's it going to
be worth after it

00:45:16.550 --> 00:45:18.010
appreciates and improves?

00:45:18.010 --> 00:45:20.050
What do you plan to do with it?

00:45:20.050 --> 00:45:22.567
If you do take the money
out and reinvest it,

00:45:22.567 --> 00:45:23.900
where are you going to reinvest?

00:45:23.900 --> 00:45:27.466
What kind of returns
are you going to get?

00:45:27.466 --> 00:45:29.340
We like tapping into
equity and utilizing it.

00:45:29.340 --> 00:45:32.580
Because we don't
necessarily want equity

00:45:32.580 --> 00:45:33.845
not doing anything for you.

00:45:33.845 --> 00:45:36.220
But you got to be smart about
it and make good decisions,

00:45:36.220 --> 00:45:37.354
obviously.

00:45:37.354 --> 00:45:39.270
AUDIENCE: So in terms
of transferring property

00:45:39.270 --> 00:45:42.040
from parents to children,
is leaving it in a trust

00:45:42.040 --> 00:45:44.634
until they die by far
the best strategy?

00:45:44.634 --> 00:45:46.300
Or are there advantages
to it otherwise?

00:45:46.300 --> 00:45:49.460
AMANDA HAN: It depends on
the net worth of the parents.

00:45:49.460 --> 00:45:52.960
So if the parents combined net
worth is under $10 million,

00:45:52.960 --> 00:45:55.964
then generally speaking,
that would be the case.

00:45:55.964 --> 00:45:58.380
Of course there's always going
to be different things that

00:45:58.380 --> 00:46:00.280
are non-tax-related
that come into play--

00:46:00.280 --> 00:46:03.130
the health of the parents,
will they need long-term care?

00:46:03.130 --> 00:46:04.669
Do they have creditors?

00:46:04.669 --> 00:46:06.460
MATTHEW MACFARLAND:
The age of the parents.

00:46:06.460 --> 00:46:08.126
AMANDA HAN: But
generally speaking, yes,

00:46:08.126 --> 00:46:11.350
under $10 million, it's better
to leave assets in the parent's

00:46:11.350 --> 00:46:12.660
name and have the kids inherit.

00:46:12.660 --> 00:46:14.160
And that's not just
for real estate.

00:46:14.160 --> 00:46:16.930
That's also with
stocks, anything

00:46:16.930 --> 00:46:18.420
that appreciates in value.

00:46:18.420 --> 00:46:20.610
And the reason for that
is when we pass away,

00:46:20.610 --> 00:46:23.110
every person get what's
called a step-up basis.

00:46:23.110 --> 00:46:25.720
So regardless of what you bought
the property or your stocks

00:46:25.720 --> 00:46:29.160
for, when you die,
the kids-- or whoever

00:46:29.160 --> 00:46:31.045
your beneficiaries
are-- will get it

00:46:31.045 --> 00:46:33.160
at whatever that day's value is.

00:46:33.160 --> 00:46:35.220
AUDIENCE: And there's no
limit to that step up?

00:46:35.220 --> 00:46:37.494
AMANDA HAN: There's no
limit to the step up, yeah.

00:46:37.494 --> 00:46:39.350
MATTHEW MACFARLAND: So I
had a client the other day

00:46:39.350 --> 00:46:40.933
who basically asked
the same question.

00:46:40.933 --> 00:46:44.500
Their parent was, I
want to say, 75, 76.

00:46:44.500 --> 00:46:48.030
And my response was no, I don't
think it makes a lot of sense.

00:46:48.030 --> 00:46:51.034
Because your parents are closer
to death than they're not.

00:46:51.034 --> 00:46:52.326
He's like, what does that mean?

00:46:52.326 --> 00:46:54.033
He's like, my parents
are in good health.

00:46:54.033 --> 00:46:55.247
And I say, well, they're 75.

00:46:55.247 --> 00:46:56.330
That means they're not 30.

00:46:56.330 --> 00:46:57.020
They're not 40.

00:46:57.020 --> 00:47:00.430
They're closer to passing away
than they were 30 years ago.

00:47:00.430 --> 00:47:04.100
And so their window for passing
away, maybe it's 5 years,

00:47:04.100 --> 00:47:05.020
maybe it's 20 years.

00:47:05.020 --> 00:47:07.320
But they're still closer
to that than they were.

00:47:07.320 --> 00:47:09.590
And so if there's a
lot of gain in there,

00:47:09.590 --> 00:47:13.440
it's hard to advise somebody to
give up on that tax-free gain

00:47:13.440 --> 00:47:17.224
that you could get 5, 10,
15 years down the road.

00:47:17.224 --> 00:47:18.890
AUDIENCE: If we have
a primary residence

00:47:18.890 --> 00:47:22.640
and also some buy and
hold rental property,

00:47:22.640 --> 00:47:26.990
can you talk about if the AMT
affects what we can deduct?

00:47:29.684 --> 00:47:31.850
MATTHEW MACFARLAND: So if
I understand the question,

00:47:31.850 --> 00:47:33.170
so you've got a
primary residence,

00:47:33.170 --> 00:47:34.930
you got a rental
property, and kind of how

00:47:34.930 --> 00:47:36.665
that plays in affecting AMT?

00:47:36.665 --> 00:47:37.290
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:47:37.290 --> 00:47:40.800
Well, if our job
makes us fall into AMT

00:47:40.800 --> 00:47:43.340
does it change any
tax strategies?

00:47:43.340 --> 00:47:46.330
MATTHEW MACFARLAND: So
AMT is just an acronym.

00:47:46.330 --> 00:47:48.405
It just means
Alternative Minimum Tax.

00:47:48.405 --> 00:47:50.080
If you're at a
30,000-foot level,

00:47:50.080 --> 00:47:54.680
it's an extra tax that the IRS
put in place about 30 years

00:47:54.680 --> 00:47:55.880
ago.

00:47:55.880 --> 00:48:00.310
It was actually put in place
so that the wealthy people

00:48:00.310 --> 00:48:03.680
of the time could stop using all
these tax loopholes they were

00:48:03.680 --> 00:48:05.480
using to avoid paying taxes.

00:48:05.480 --> 00:48:08.620
And so they were trying to put
in place a minimum level of tax

00:48:08.620 --> 00:48:10.050
that they wanted people to pay.

00:48:10.050 --> 00:48:15.454
And so unfortunately for
people who live in California,

00:48:15.454 --> 00:48:17.120
it's kind of like a
parallel tax system.

00:48:17.120 --> 00:48:19.078
One of the things that's
not deductible for AMT

00:48:19.078 --> 00:48:20.600
is state income taxes.

00:48:20.600 --> 00:48:22.950
And California and New
York are the two states

00:48:22.950 --> 00:48:24.658
that have the highest
state income taxes.

00:48:24.658 --> 00:48:26.760
Your highest rate
here is like, 13%.

00:48:26.760 --> 00:48:31.970
So generally speaking, if
a taxpayer in California

00:48:31.970 --> 00:48:36.830
is making $150,000
to $300,000 a year

00:48:36.830 --> 00:48:40.590
and paying a good
chunk in state taxes,

00:48:40.590 --> 00:48:42.630
they're probably going
to be an AMT, whether you

00:48:42.630 --> 00:48:44.840
have a rental property or not.

00:48:44.840 --> 00:48:50.216
And so there's things you can
do for AMT, to plan for it.

00:48:50.216 --> 00:48:52.100
But just from a
reality standpoint,

00:48:52.100 --> 00:48:54.770
people who live in
California are making

00:48:54.770 --> 00:48:57.737
six figures, single
or married, there's

00:48:57.737 --> 00:48:59.195
a very high likelihood
you're going

00:48:59.195 --> 00:49:02.780
to fall into AMT, whether you
have a rental property or even

00:49:02.780 --> 00:49:04.031
a primary residence sometimes.

00:49:04.031 --> 00:49:05.405
AMANDA HAN: Yeah,
I mean, I think

00:49:05.405 --> 00:49:07.450
we don't see rental real
estate as an adjustment

00:49:07.450 --> 00:49:10.250
either for or against AMT.

00:49:10.250 --> 00:49:14.420
For all of us here, the biggest
thing that changes that number

00:49:14.420 --> 00:49:15.530
is state taxes.

00:49:15.530 --> 00:49:17.360
And unfortunately,
there's not much you

00:49:17.360 --> 00:49:21.337
can do in terms of state tax,
from your W-2 job, at least.

00:49:21.337 --> 00:49:23.420
It's going to be withheld
based on whatever it is.

00:49:23.420 --> 00:49:26.003
AUDIENCE: The first one is you
mentioned that we can write off

00:49:26.003 --> 00:49:31.310
the cost of, for example,
looking for property to invest,

00:49:31.310 --> 00:49:31.820
right?

00:49:31.820 --> 00:49:36.450
So is this applicable to
foreign countries also?

00:49:36.450 --> 00:49:39.370
Or is it only for USA?

00:49:39.370 --> 00:49:42.130
AMANDA HAN: No, it's applicable
to foreign countries as well.

00:49:42.130 --> 00:49:44.980
Now, with any kind
of travel cost,

00:49:44.980 --> 00:49:47.820
the key thing that you want
to make sure you have in place

00:49:47.820 --> 00:49:50.850
is predetermined
business purpose.

00:49:50.850 --> 00:49:52.420
So what we mean by
that is if you're

00:49:52.420 --> 00:49:54.200
going to fly to
Asia, for example,

00:49:54.200 --> 00:49:56.230
you're visiting
family, you happen

00:49:56.230 --> 00:49:58.400
to look at some real
estate, that does not

00:49:58.400 --> 00:50:00.400
make the trip tax deductible.

00:50:00.400 --> 00:50:04.240
Because you were on a trip and
you happened to do real estate.

00:50:04.240 --> 00:50:05.880
In order for it
to be deductible,

00:50:05.880 --> 00:50:09.930
you have to have documentation
to show that maybe I scheduled

00:50:09.930 --> 00:50:11.760
these meetings to meet
with these people,

00:50:11.760 --> 00:50:13.809
to look at these properties
before you leave.

00:50:13.809 --> 00:50:16.100
And the reason, if you think
of it from the IRS's side,

00:50:16.100 --> 00:50:17.800
and say, well, why
did you go to Asia?

00:50:17.800 --> 00:50:20.300
Well, I went there because I
had all these business meetings

00:50:20.300 --> 00:50:22.480
that I had pre-scheduled.

00:50:22.480 --> 00:50:26.470
And so that's the same out of
the country, in the country,

00:50:26.470 --> 00:50:28.510
going down to
Southern California.

00:50:28.510 --> 00:50:30.640
It's always that same
underlying concept

00:50:30.640 --> 00:50:33.530
of what is the
reason I went there?

00:50:33.530 --> 00:50:34.690
AUDIENCE: OK, thank you.

00:50:34.690 --> 00:50:38.190
So my second question
is how can we

00:50:38.190 --> 00:50:44.920
write off the cost on the time
we spend for rental purpose?

00:50:44.920 --> 00:50:47.650
It's not like for
home improvement.

00:50:47.650 --> 00:50:49.810
We have receipt
but we don't have

00:50:49.810 --> 00:50:51.690
this for the time we spend.

00:50:51.690 --> 00:50:53.440
AMANDA HAN: That's a
really good question.

00:50:53.440 --> 00:50:54.190
We get that a lot.

00:50:54.190 --> 00:50:56.760
Unfortunately, the
answer is not a good one.

00:50:56.760 --> 00:50:58.470
So the way that--

00:50:58.470 --> 00:50:59.682
MATTHEW MACFARLAND: You know,
you asked the right way,

00:50:59.682 --> 00:50:59.990
"How can I?"

00:50:59.990 --> 00:51:00.140
But--

00:51:00.140 --> 00:51:00.440
[LAUGHS]

00:51:00.440 --> 00:51:01.273
AUDIENCE: How can I?

00:51:01.273 --> 00:51:01.809
[LAUGHS]

00:51:01.809 --> 00:51:02.850
AMANDA HAN: So you can't.

00:51:02.850 --> 00:51:04.520
OK, I'll re-answer this.

00:51:04.520 --> 00:51:05.600
So you can.

00:51:05.600 --> 00:51:07.880
However, you would have to
pick up that same dollar

00:51:07.880 --> 00:51:09.470
amount as income.

00:51:09.470 --> 00:51:11.760
So that just means,
for example, if you

00:51:11.760 --> 00:51:14.160
hired me to do your
house improvements,

00:51:14.160 --> 00:51:15.890
you write off what you pay me.

00:51:15.890 --> 00:51:17.780
But I pick that up
in taxable income,

00:51:17.780 --> 00:51:19.040
because I earn the money.

00:51:19.040 --> 00:51:21.270
And so if you wanted
to pay yourself,

00:51:21.270 --> 00:51:22.700
you can certainly do that.

00:51:22.700 --> 00:51:24.440
We don't recommend
it for anyone at all.

00:51:24.440 --> 00:51:27.080
Because you're just
writing off and picking up

00:51:27.080 --> 00:51:28.800
income in the same
exact dollar amount.

00:51:28.800 --> 00:51:31.240
And I know people would
say, well, I value my time.

00:51:31.240 --> 00:51:35.640
Maybe I charge $100 an hour
or $500 an hour to my clients.

00:51:35.640 --> 00:51:37.140
But I can't charge myself.

00:51:37.140 --> 00:51:39.550
I mean, I can, but
it's just a wash.

00:51:39.550 --> 00:51:41.855
So we don't really
factor that as a cost.

00:51:41.855 --> 00:51:43.355
MATTHEW MACFARLAND:
Similar question

00:51:43.355 --> 00:51:46.155
we get is I donate 10
hours a month to charity

00:51:46.155 --> 00:51:48.204
and I value my time
at $200 an hour.

00:51:48.204 --> 00:51:50.620
So I think I should be able
to take a charitable deduction

00:51:50.620 --> 00:51:52.060
for that value.

00:51:52.060 --> 00:51:54.562
And unfortunately, you can't.

00:51:54.562 --> 00:51:56.520
AMANDA HAN: But you can
deduct all the supplies

00:51:56.520 --> 00:51:58.995
and travel costs for all
your charitable work.

00:51:58.995 --> 00:52:00.370
MATTHEW MACFARLAND:
Right, right.

00:52:00.370 --> 00:52:02.830
AUDIENCE: If you have rental
income property in San

00:52:02.830 --> 00:52:07.970
Francisco, and you have tenants
who pay below-market-rate rent,

00:52:07.970 --> 00:52:09.710
is the amount that
you would pay them

00:52:09.710 --> 00:52:12.220
to move out tax deductible?

00:52:12.220 --> 00:52:13.420
AMANDA HAN: Oh, mhm, yes.

00:52:13.420 --> 00:52:13.950
Yeah.

00:52:13.950 --> 00:52:16.354
So you mean, kind of
like cash for keys?

00:52:16.354 --> 00:52:18.020
When you pay them to
have them move out?

00:52:18.020 --> 00:52:19.380
Yes, that is definitely
a tax deduction.

00:52:19.380 --> 00:52:20.120
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:52:20.120 --> 00:52:20.530
AMANDA HAN: Yeah.

00:52:20.530 --> 00:52:22.750
Unfortunately, we see that
more often than we'd like.

00:52:22.750 --> 00:52:24.970
[LAUGHS]

00:52:24.970 --> 00:52:26.970
AUDIENCE: So you guys
mentioned that there's not

00:52:26.970 --> 00:52:29.907
real difference in tax
benefits between LLC

00:52:29.907 --> 00:52:32.160
and just holding
it in your name.

00:52:32.160 --> 00:52:33.950
Is that also true if
you're trying to buy

00:52:33.950 --> 00:52:35.790
properties with a
50/50 partnership?

00:52:38.650 --> 00:52:40.786
AMANDA HAN: Well, so
it depends on what

00:52:40.786 --> 00:52:42.412
is the intent for the property?

00:52:42.412 --> 00:52:43.370
AUDIENCE: Buy and hold.

00:52:43.370 --> 00:52:45.078
AMANDA HAN: If it's
a rental real estate,

00:52:45.078 --> 00:52:47.890
it's neutral for tax purposes.

00:52:47.890 --> 00:52:50.670
Then the only reason
you would have an LLC

00:52:50.670 --> 00:52:54.130
is if you have asset
protection concerns

00:52:54.130 --> 00:52:55.350
with that particular partner.

00:52:55.350 --> 00:52:57.550
So kind of going back to the
other example, with the sister.

00:52:57.550 --> 00:52:58.059
Right?

00:52:58.059 --> 00:52:59.600
My sister, she's
not going to sue me.

00:52:59.600 --> 00:53:00.694
I'm not going to sue her.

00:53:00.694 --> 00:53:02.110
If something were
to happen to me,

00:53:02.110 --> 00:53:03.480
we know each other's wishes.

00:53:03.480 --> 00:53:05.590
You might not need it.

00:53:05.590 --> 00:53:08.560
If it's with another coworker,
or even a more distant family

00:53:08.560 --> 00:53:11.490
member or friend, you might
want to have a partnership

00:53:11.490 --> 00:53:14.595
if there is an asset protection
concern between the two of you.

00:53:14.595 --> 00:53:15.970
MATTHEW MACFARLAND:
Another thing

00:53:15.970 --> 00:53:18.570
I should add to that is one
situation where it might make

00:53:18.570 --> 00:53:20.960
a difference is let's
say, you're going

00:53:20.960 --> 00:53:23.650
to buy it individually, 50/50.

00:53:23.650 --> 00:53:25.760
Legally you're probably
going to own it as what's

00:53:25.760 --> 00:53:27.100
called tenants in common.

00:53:27.100 --> 00:53:30.180
So for tax purposes, that
means you own 50% of it.

00:53:30.180 --> 00:53:31.740
You have to report
50% of the income

00:53:31.740 --> 00:53:34.150
and report 50% of the expenses.

00:53:34.150 --> 00:53:37.130
Whether or not you actually
collected 50% or not,

00:53:37.130 --> 00:53:38.350
maybe she collected 100%.

00:53:38.350 --> 00:53:40.550
You still have to report 50%.

00:53:40.550 --> 00:53:43.010
Now, so let's take that
to the other situation.

00:53:43.010 --> 00:53:47.700
Maybe you want ways to
say, OK, we own it 50/50.

00:53:47.700 --> 00:53:51.970
But I'm going to 75% of
the expenses and the losses

00:53:51.970 --> 00:53:54.410
for the next five
years, until we sell it.

00:53:54.410 --> 00:53:57.900
Then we'll even it
out in the back end.

00:53:57.900 --> 00:54:01.652
If you want to be able to
do that, then doing an LLC

00:54:01.652 --> 00:54:03.860
would be the way to go,
versus the tenants in common.

00:54:03.860 --> 00:54:06.340
Because you wouldn't be able to
do that as tenants in common.

00:54:06.340 --> 00:54:07.256
So it kind of depends.

00:54:07.256 --> 00:54:09.820
If you're planning to
share things 50/50, other

00:54:09.820 --> 00:54:11.913
than the asset protection,
it makes no difference.

00:54:11.913 --> 00:54:12.581
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:54:12.581 --> 00:54:14.330
AMANDA HAN: I mean,
just one little tidbit

00:54:14.330 --> 00:54:17.090
to throw out-- legal entities,
I know we talked quite a bit

00:54:17.090 --> 00:54:18.120
about that.

00:54:18.120 --> 00:54:20.320
Timing is also important.

00:54:20.320 --> 00:54:26.010
So for California, the $800
fee is not a pro-rated amount.

00:54:26.010 --> 00:54:27.940
Let's say, you felt like,
I do want that asset

00:54:27.940 --> 00:54:30.300
protection from my partner,
we're talking about.

00:54:30.300 --> 00:54:32.316
So now we're close to September.

00:54:32.316 --> 00:54:33.690
Let's say, by the
time you decide

00:54:33.690 --> 00:54:36.310
to go into this deal it's
going to be November.

00:54:36.310 --> 00:54:38.175
And so if you form an
entity in November,

00:54:38.175 --> 00:54:39.826
you're going to pay
$800 for this year.

00:54:39.826 --> 00:54:42.200
And then you're going to pay
another $800 come next year.

00:54:42.200 --> 00:54:44.660
So you're really only
getting that benefit

00:54:44.660 --> 00:54:46.690
for a one-month period.

00:54:46.690 --> 00:54:48.004
So timing is also important.

00:54:48.004 --> 00:54:49.420
If it's the beginning
of the year,

00:54:49.420 --> 00:54:51.628
you're pretty sure this is
going to happen, you know,

00:54:51.628 --> 00:54:53.400
I would say, go
ahead and form it.

00:54:53.400 --> 00:54:55.046
But right now, you
just want to be

00:54:55.046 --> 00:54:57.990
cautious of time frame of how
long you're going that benefit,

00:54:57.990 --> 00:55:03.745
before you have to pay
that second round of $800.

00:55:03.745 --> 00:55:05.120
JORDAN THIBODEAU:
A lot of people

00:55:05.120 --> 00:55:07.625
