00:57:42.820 --> 00:57:44.820
JORDAN THIBODEAU: From
Chris-- "My understanding

00:57:44.820 --> 00:57:50.390
is that deductible rental losses
phase out at $150,000 of income

00:57:50.390 --> 00:57:52.840
if not pursuing real
estate as a career.

00:57:52.840 --> 00:57:55.060
Do most wealthy individuals
accept this fact

00:57:55.060 --> 00:57:58.370
and wait until the sale of a
property and apply the loss?

00:57:58.370 --> 00:58:01.510
Or are there other workarounds
for this limitation?"

00:58:01.510 --> 00:58:03.260
MATTHEW MACFARLAND:
It's a great question.

00:58:03.260 --> 00:58:06.814
So just to kind
of paraphrase it,

00:58:06.814 --> 00:58:08.230
we were talking
earlier about when

00:58:08.230 --> 00:58:09.720
we have cash-flow
positive properties,

00:58:09.720 --> 00:58:11.094
but if we can get
enough expenses

00:58:11.094 --> 00:58:13.510
and get a loss on paper
for that rental property?

00:58:13.510 --> 00:58:15.720
Well, the IRS will say, yes,
you can deduct that loss

00:58:15.720 --> 00:58:17.470
against your other income.

00:58:17.470 --> 00:58:21.940
But if your income gets to
be $150,000 or more per year,

00:58:21.940 --> 00:58:24.845
that takes away your ability
to deduct that loss this year.

00:58:24.845 --> 00:58:26.470
Now, you get to carry
forward the loss.

00:58:26.470 --> 00:58:27.600
You don't lose it.

00:58:27.600 --> 00:58:29.433
And that's what the
question's referring to.

00:58:29.433 --> 00:58:31.981
Do people just wait around
and use it in the year

00:58:31.981 --> 00:58:33.730
that they sell the
property down the road?

00:58:33.730 --> 00:58:36.862
And that's what some people do.

00:58:36.862 --> 00:58:38.570
Another option is
people actually started

00:58:38.570 --> 00:58:41.500
reinvesting money to
generating better cash flow

00:58:41.500 --> 00:58:44.470
properties that they have
positive income on the tax

00:58:44.470 --> 00:58:46.220
return, that they can
utilize their losses

00:58:46.220 --> 00:58:49.020
from the other properties
to offset that.

00:58:49.020 --> 00:58:52.170
That's one avenue
we've seen people do.

00:58:52.170 --> 00:58:54.460
Or become a real
estate professional,

00:58:54.460 --> 00:58:57.290
where going forward, that
limitation goes out the window.

00:58:57.290 --> 00:58:59.517
Because now you are in
the day-to-day business,

00:58:59.517 --> 00:59:02.100
whether it's you, or maybe your
spouse or something like that.

00:59:02.100 --> 00:59:05.750
So it's an unfortunate
limitation,

00:59:05.750 --> 00:59:08.290
because it's been
in place since 1986,

00:59:08.290 --> 00:59:09.922
and the numbers haven't changed.

00:59:09.922 --> 00:59:13.362
And it's crazy because
obviously in California, you

00:59:13.362 --> 00:59:16.272
can get to that income pretty
quickly for a lot of people.

00:59:16.272 --> 00:59:18.100
AMANDA HAN: Yeah.

00:59:18.100 --> 00:59:22.617
And you know, the person that
asked the question mentioned,

00:59:22.617 --> 00:59:24.700
besides the fact, that you
could do it if you have

00:59:24.700 --> 00:59:26.337
real estate as your career.

00:59:26.337 --> 00:59:28.170
I think that that's a
little bit misleading.

00:59:28.170 --> 00:59:30.000
Because to be a real
estate professional,

00:59:30.000 --> 00:59:33.030
it does not mean you have to
become a realtor or broker

00:59:33.030 --> 00:59:34.570
or get licensed.

00:59:34.570 --> 00:59:38.786
Real estate professional is only
a term used in the tax world.

00:59:38.786 --> 00:59:40.160
And that simply
means that you're

00:59:40.160 --> 00:59:42.020
spending more time
in real estate

00:59:42.020 --> 00:59:44.200
than you are at your jobs.

00:59:44.200 --> 00:59:47.060
So now if you guys are
working full time here,

00:59:47.060 --> 00:59:48.190
that means 40 hours a week.

00:59:48.190 --> 00:59:49.260
So to be a real
estate professional,

00:59:49.260 --> 00:59:50.843
you got to be working
41 hours a week.

00:59:50.843 --> 00:59:52.950
So yes, that is very hard.

00:59:52.950 --> 00:59:55.340
But what if you have
a stay-at-home spouse?

00:59:55.340 --> 00:59:57.790
If you had a stay-at-home
spouse and they're just

00:59:57.790 --> 01:00:00.850
really watching the kids, doing
household things, then really,

01:00:00.850 --> 01:00:02.600
for them to be a real
estate professional,

01:00:02.600 --> 01:00:06.460
they only have to spend at
least 750 hours in real estate.

01:00:06.460 --> 01:00:10.180
And once they reach that
goal, then collectively,

01:00:10.180 --> 01:00:13.380
you guys get to use the
benefits of the rental losses

01:00:13.380 --> 01:00:15.450
in this guy's situation.

01:00:15.450 --> 01:00:16.770
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:00:16.770 --> 01:00:19.140
AMANDA HAN: The question is
how do you document the time

01:00:19.140 --> 01:00:20.980
that you're incurring?

01:00:20.980 --> 01:00:24.600
So the IRS doesn't have
a specific requirement.

01:00:24.600 --> 01:00:26.650
They don't have a form
or anything like that.

01:00:26.650 --> 01:00:29.700
The only thing they require
is a consistent methodology.

01:00:29.700 --> 01:00:32.081
Meaning if you use
a notepad, they

01:00:32.081 --> 01:00:34.080
want you to use that
notepad for the whole year.

01:00:34.080 --> 01:00:38.130
Or if going to be your calendar,
something written in Excel,

01:00:38.130 --> 01:00:40.080
it just has to be consistent.

01:00:40.080 --> 01:00:43.142
Really, the time tracking
doesn't get sent to anywhere.

01:00:43.142 --> 01:00:45.600
For our clients who claim real
estate, we don't look at it.

01:00:45.600 --> 01:00:48.230
We don't audit
that kind of stuff.

01:00:48.230 --> 01:00:50.580
The only time you will
be required to produce it

01:00:50.580 --> 01:00:53.157
is if you were to be
audited by the IRS.

01:00:53.157 --> 01:00:54.740
Let's say you were
selected for audit.

01:00:54.740 --> 01:00:56.720
And they say, well,
I'm really not sure

01:00:56.720 --> 01:00:58.240
if you qualify as real estate.

01:00:58.240 --> 01:00:59.407
I want to see your time log.

01:00:59.407 --> 01:01:01.656
And what they'll do, is
they'll look at your time log.

01:01:01.656 --> 01:01:03.960
It might have hundreds of
entries for the whole year,

01:01:03.960 --> 01:01:04.580
right?

01:01:04.580 --> 01:01:05.990
And then what they'll
do is they'll go through

01:01:05.990 --> 01:01:08.046
and they'll do what's
called sample selection.

01:01:08.046 --> 01:01:09.420
They're going to
say, OK you said

01:01:09.420 --> 01:01:13.380
you spent two hours at Google,
listening to a real estate tax

01:01:13.380 --> 01:01:14.160
talk.

01:01:14.160 --> 01:01:15.220
Prove it.

01:01:15.220 --> 01:01:17.960
So hopefully you have
something-- an e-mail,

01:01:17.960 --> 01:01:22.070
or your coworkers can vouch
for you-- that you were here.

01:01:22.070 --> 01:01:26.430
In audits that we've dealt
with, thankfully, the agents

01:01:26.430 --> 01:01:29.150
on the IRS's side have
been pretty reasonable,

01:01:29.150 --> 01:01:31.140
in that they would
select things that they

01:01:31.140 --> 01:01:32.520
think could be proven.

01:01:32.520 --> 01:01:34.930
So that would mean you went
to Colorado for a real estate

01:01:34.930 --> 01:01:36.610
conference for three days.

01:01:36.610 --> 01:01:39.510
OK, you should have something
that showed me you were there

01:01:39.510 --> 01:01:41.460
doing the real estate seminar.

01:01:41.460 --> 01:01:42.960
MATTHEW MACFARLAND:
So really you're

01:01:42.960 --> 01:01:45.580
trying to keep of
a date, obviously,

01:01:45.580 --> 01:01:48.480
a description of what you
do, a description of who

01:01:48.480 --> 01:01:50.712
you met with, what you
talked about, obviously

01:01:50.712 --> 01:01:51.920
the amount of time you spent.

01:01:51.920 --> 01:01:54.810
Those are the most
important aspects of it.

01:01:54.810 --> 01:01:56.816
And again, however
you keep of it,

01:01:56.816 --> 01:01:58.690
it doesn't matter as
long at it's consistent.

01:01:58.690 --> 01:02:00.710
AUDIENCE: What
