01:04:24.830 --> 01:04:27.160
Unless you are someone
very well versed

01:04:27.160 --> 01:04:30.060
in the rules of self-directed,
it's very easy for you

01:04:30.060 --> 01:04:31.190
to get yourself in trouble.

01:04:31.190 --> 01:04:33.040
Because when you use
that, we don't see it.

01:04:33.040 --> 01:04:34.940
There's no custodian
that sees it.

01:04:34.940 --> 01:04:38.980
So it's just more
open to mishaps.

01:04:38.980 --> 01:04:40.670
The other thing
is, Matt and I went

01:04:40.670 --> 01:04:44.600
to a self-directed training
a couple years ago,

01:04:44.600 --> 01:04:46.470
where one of the
directors from the IRS

01:04:46.470 --> 01:04:48.269
was one of the speakers.

01:04:48.269 --> 01:04:49.810
And they did say,
that there is going

01:04:49.810 --> 01:04:53.242
to be a heavier effort on their
end to audit these checkbook

01:04:53.242 --> 01:04:55.946
IRAs for that exact reason.

01:04:55.946 --> 01:04:57.820
They know that's a lot
of money, potentially,

01:04:57.820 --> 01:05:00.520
they can come after, if you make
a small mistake by accident.

01:05:00.520 --> 01:05:02.920
Because with self directed,
like we were saying earlier,

01:05:02.920 --> 01:05:04.750
you can invest in almost
anything you want.

01:05:04.750 --> 01:05:07.140
But there's a lot of
things that you "can't do,"

01:05:07.140 --> 01:05:09.515
even after you get
your investment.

01:05:09.515 --> 01:05:11.690
So it's supposed to be a
retirement account where

01:05:11.690 --> 01:05:15.670
you kind of let it do its thing,
for lack of a better term.

01:05:15.670 --> 01:05:17.160
So there's a lot
of things you've

01:05:17.160 --> 01:05:18.410
got to keep your hands off of.

01:05:18.410 --> 01:05:22.290
And that's where there's a lot
of abuse right now, I think.

01:05:22.290 --> 01:05:25.360
AUDIENCE: So I bought
a property recently.

01:05:25.360 --> 01:05:28.190
And I had cash just
that I had saved.

01:05:28.190 --> 01:05:33.080
And I wanted to invest outside
of the stock and bonds,

01:05:33.080 --> 01:05:34.835
so just diversify.

01:05:34.835 --> 01:05:36.460
And then the big
question is, well, you

01:05:36.460 --> 01:05:40.550
buy a place for like, in this
case, it was $1.1 million.

01:05:40.550 --> 01:05:43.669
And then how much
cash do you put down?

01:05:43.669 --> 01:05:45.710
You don't really want to
take too much of a loss,

01:05:45.710 --> 01:05:48.630
because we can't write
it off as let's say,

01:05:48.630 --> 01:05:50.220
as good income earners.

01:05:50.220 --> 01:05:53.010
But then you don't want to
be paying money out of pocket

01:05:53.010 --> 01:05:54.150
every month either.

01:05:54.150 --> 01:05:58.305
So I just took a ballpark and
said, well, I'll put down 50%.

01:06:02.160 --> 01:06:04.230
And I'll get a loan
on the other 50%.

01:06:04.230 --> 01:06:07.120
And that would
basically break even.

01:06:07.120 --> 01:06:11.120
And I'm just
wondering, I usually

01:06:11.120 --> 01:06:12.350
go with the 50/50 strategy.

01:06:12.350 --> 01:06:14.306
But what do you
recommend in this case?

01:06:14.306 --> 01:06:16.180
Of course now I have a
lot of capital tied up

01:06:16.180 --> 01:06:17.793
into one property.

01:06:17.793 --> 01:06:19.060
AMANDA HAN: Yeah.

01:06:19.060 --> 01:06:20.840
I think it really depends.

01:06:20.840 --> 01:06:22.590
I mean, the answer's
going to be different

01:06:22.590 --> 01:06:23.700
for every single person.

01:06:23.700 --> 01:06:28.560
So for you, the options
would be to put less down

01:06:28.560 --> 01:06:30.105
and carry more debt.

01:06:30.105 --> 01:06:33.785
So if you did that, instead
of putting 50%, if you put 20%

01:06:33.785 --> 01:06:35.790
and you did two
rental properties,

01:06:35.790 --> 01:06:37.305
what would be the
return on that?

01:06:37.305 --> 01:06:42.020
It's a higher risk because you
have more debt to worry about.

01:06:42.020 --> 01:06:44.120
So the risk tolerance
level does come into play.

01:06:44.120 --> 01:06:46.040
We were talking about
that earlier at lunch.

01:06:46.040 --> 01:06:51.774
And so I think at the end the
day, for me as an investor,

01:06:51.774 --> 01:06:52.690
I look at the numbers.

01:06:52.690 --> 01:06:54.650
I look at the worst-case
scenario for me.

01:06:54.650 --> 01:06:56.800
And I would say, OK, in
the worst-case scenario,

01:06:56.800 --> 01:06:57.420
would I be OK?

01:06:57.420 --> 01:06:58.870
Would I be able
to carry this debt

01:06:58.870 --> 01:07:00.450
on this particular property?

01:07:00.450 --> 01:07:03.309
And if that answer is yes,
then I'm comfortable with it.

01:07:03.309 --> 01:07:05.350
We have a lot of clients
that are more high risk.

01:07:05.350 --> 01:07:06.570
They want to put
the minimum down.

01:07:06.570 --> 01:07:08.640
They want to get as many
properties as possible.

01:07:08.640 --> 01:07:10.196
Maybe because
they're really young,

01:07:10.196 --> 01:07:11.279
they're just starting out.

01:07:11.279 --> 01:07:13.440
They feel like this is the
time to take the gamble.

01:07:13.440 --> 01:07:14.898
Don't want to wait
until I'm almost

01:07:14.898 --> 01:07:16.325
retiring to take that gamble.

01:07:16.325 --> 01:07:18.325
So those are the factors
that you're looking at.

01:07:18.325 --> 01:07:23.490
I don't think there's a correct
answer to 20% versus 50%.

01:07:23.490 --> 01:07:25.770
AUDIENCE: Well, I mean, one
thing I think we all see

01:07:25.770 --> 01:07:27.950
here is it's pretty
difficult to buy,

01:07:27.950 --> 01:07:31.650
let's say, rental properties
and even break even.

01:07:31.650 --> 01:07:34.900
It's just the factors aren't
here, especially in California.

01:07:34.900 --> 01:07:38.320
So I know it's kind of
outside of tax advice.

01:07:38.320 --> 01:07:41.630
But where do you see your
active real estate investors,

01:07:41.630 --> 01:07:43.220
or buy and hold real
estate investors,

01:07:43.220 --> 01:07:45.730
where are they buying
now, to make numbers

01:07:45.730 --> 01:07:47.750
add up to where you said?

01:07:47.750 --> 01:07:49.904
MATTHEW MACFARLAND: We
have a lot of clients

01:07:49.904 --> 01:07:51.510
buy throughout the countries.

01:07:51.510 --> 01:07:54.810
So we've got a lot of
clients that buy in Texas,

01:07:54.810 --> 01:07:58.265
Georgia, Tennessee, Ohio.

01:07:58.265 --> 01:07:59.682
AMANDA HAN: Yeah, Ohio.

01:07:59.682 --> 01:08:01.640
I mean, I don't know the
market in Ohio at all.

01:08:01.640 --> 01:08:03.806
But yes, I have a lot of
people that have cashed out

01:08:03.806 --> 01:08:05.640
of California, going into Ohio.

01:08:05.640 --> 01:08:07.497
I think that good
and bad is they

01:08:07.497 --> 01:08:09.080
take the appreciation
from California,

01:08:09.080 --> 01:08:10.950
and they move to Ohio.

01:08:10.950 --> 01:08:13.670
There, there's probably not
going to be much appreciation.

01:08:13.670 --> 01:08:15.290
but what they're
getting is cash flow.

01:08:15.290 --> 01:08:16.762
So that's a personal question.

01:08:16.762 --> 01:08:17.970
What's more important to you?

01:08:17.970 --> 01:08:20.095
Do you need the cash flow
to live off of right now?

01:08:20.095 --> 01:08:20.689
Probably not.

01:08:20.689 --> 01:08:23.290
So would you rather
have the appreciation?

01:08:23.290 --> 01:08:25.960
Another area that we have
a lot of clients going into

01:08:25.960 --> 01:08:26.910
is Florida.

01:08:26.910 --> 01:08:28.810
So from what I hear,
our clients that

01:08:28.810 --> 01:08:31.155
are full-time active
real estate investors,

01:08:31.155 --> 01:08:34.890
it sounds like Florida today
is kind of where California

01:08:34.890 --> 01:08:36.452
was maybe two, three years ago.

01:08:36.452 --> 01:08:37.910
So people are still
flipping there.

01:08:37.910 --> 01:08:39.159
They're still doing wholesale.

01:08:39.159 --> 01:08:41.890
Wholesale is almost
impossible to get here.

01:08:41.890 --> 01:08:43.090
Because there's no margins.

01:08:43.090 --> 01:08:44.050
AUDIENCE: What's wholesale?

01:08:44.050 --> 01:08:45.970
AMANDA HAN: Wholesale
is when I get a property

01:08:45.970 --> 01:08:48.630
under contract at a good price.

01:08:48.630 --> 01:08:50.784
And then maybe I
wholesale it to you.

01:08:50.784 --> 01:08:52.950
You buy it and then you
either turn it into a rental

01:08:52.950 --> 01:08:54.340
or you're going to
do a fix and flip,

01:08:54.340 --> 01:08:55.290
and you're going to rehab it.

01:08:55.290 --> 01:08:56.620
MATTHEW MACFARLAND:
And she gets a--

01:08:56.620 --> 01:08:56.859
AMANDA HAN: And I
get a wholesale fee.

01:08:56.859 --> 01:08:59.404
MATTHEW MACFARLAND: --$5,000
wholesale fee for doing

01:08:59.404 --> 01:09:00.529
the transaction, basically.

01:09:00.529 --> 01:09:01.649
AMANDA HAN: Kind of
like a finder's fee.

01:09:01.649 --> 01:09:03.720
So those kind of deals
only work when there's

01:09:03.720 --> 01:09:05.160
a healthy margin in the profit.

01:09:05.160 --> 01:09:09.010
That's why we don't really see
a ton of that in California.

01:09:09.010 --> 01:09:10.649
But yeah, some of
those other states,

01:09:10.649 --> 01:09:13.701
like Matt mentioned, Georgia,
Tennessee, Texas, Florida,

01:09:13.701 --> 01:09:15.197
Ohio.

01:09:15.197 --> 01:09:17.155
AUDIENCE: For someone
who's always just kind of

01:09:17.155 --> 01:09:19.069
bought Turbo Tax and
winged it, can you

01:09:19.069 --> 01:09:22.229
talk a little bit about what
a typical interaction is

01:09:22.229 --> 01:09:24.569
with a CPA, like, aside
from just filing taxes?

01:09:24.569 --> 01:09:26.753
What kind of time
and expense is there

01:09:26.753 --> 01:09:28.711
throughout the year, and
planning and strategy,

01:09:28.711 --> 01:09:31.443
and stuff like that?

01:09:31.443 --> 01:09:33.109
AMANDA HAN: I think
it's going to differ

01:09:33.109 --> 01:09:34.560
with every single firm.

01:09:34.560 --> 01:09:37.880
For us, our emphasis is on
tax planning side of things.

01:09:37.880 --> 01:09:41.300
So we have clients that come to
us for planning and tax return.

01:09:41.300 --> 01:09:45.710
Or we have clients that come
to us just for planning.

01:09:45.710 --> 01:09:49.170
So like I said earlier, the
planning part-- if you've never

01:09:49.170 --> 01:09:52.700
done planning before, if
you've always done it yourself,

01:09:52.700 --> 01:09:55.620
I highly recommend you invest
the time and the energy

01:09:55.620 --> 01:09:59.270
to do at least one comprehensive
planning so you have a roadmap

01:09:59.270 --> 01:10:02.350
to follow on what some of
those high-level items are.

01:10:02.350 --> 01:10:06.240
But the reality is
that is going to be

01:10:06.240 --> 01:10:07.720
kind of a living document.

01:10:07.720 --> 01:10:10.070
Because today you have
these sets of rentals.

01:10:10.070 --> 01:10:12.670
Tomorrow you might go
into a multifamily.

01:10:12.670 --> 01:10:15.140
And so the strategy
itself will be changing

01:10:15.140 --> 01:10:16.540
throughout the years as well.

01:10:16.540 --> 01:10:19.540
I think the most effective
planning is really

01:10:19.540 --> 01:10:22.410
just open communication,
as easy as that sounds.

01:10:22.410 --> 01:10:24.220
Because really, the
goal is not for you

01:10:24.220 --> 01:10:26.990
guys to understand everything
there is to know about taxes,

01:10:26.990 --> 01:10:30.080
and be updated with all the
various tax changes that

01:10:30.080 --> 01:10:31.170
come out during the year.

01:10:31.170 --> 01:10:33.050
That's your CPA's job.

01:10:33.050 --> 01:10:36.170
But your job, really, is just
to keep them updated on anything

01:10:36.170 --> 01:10:37.721
that you think
might be changing.

01:10:37.721 --> 01:10:38.720
I might be buying a car.

01:10:38.720 --> 01:10:40.100
I might be getting married.

01:10:40.100 --> 01:10:41.310
I might be getting a divorce.

01:10:41.310 --> 01:10:44.120
Those are times when there
could be a lot of money

01:10:44.120 --> 01:10:47.050
at play, shifting of money.

01:10:47.050 --> 01:10:50.370
That's the times when they will
be able to help and guide you

01:10:50.370 --> 01:10:53.735
on what are some of the
things to keep in mind.

01:10:53.735 --> 01:10:55.110
JORDAN THIBODEAU:
Well, thank you

01:10:55.110 --> 01:10:56.704
very much for coming through.

